# Spec 0022 ‚Äî Berreman Optical Constructor ‚Äî Solution architecture & cross-cutting contract

## 0. Binding constraints

The following constraints are normative for EVERY part (A‚ÄìJ) of this specification. A directive in any later part that conflicts with one of these is void.

1. **Platform & language commitment.** The solution MUST target **.NET 10** and MUST be **F#-first** end to end: engine, orchestration, UI, and tooling are all F#. The domain model MUST be expressed as F# records and discriminated unions. C# projects are admitted ONLY where they already exist in the Berreman tree as cloned dependencies (`../MathNetNumerics/Numerics/Numerics.csproj`, cited at `C:/GitHub/Berreman/Berreman/Berreman.slnx:8`). No part MAY introduce a new C# project.

2. **Reuse before invention.** Every directive that touches an area already served by a Berreman primitive MUST name and call that primitive rather than re-implementing it, and MUST cite it as `<file>:<symbol>` or `<file>:<line>`. New modules, files, or abstractions are admitted ONLY when they trace to a named directive in this spec; a new artefact with no such trace MUST be dropped. The 4√ó4 solver (`Solvers.fs` `OpticalSystemSolver`), the field model (`Fields.fs` `EmFieldSystem`), the tensor model (`MaterialProperties.fs` `OpticalProperties`), and the units constants (`Constants.fs`) MUST NOT be forked, re-derived, or shadowed.

3. **Canonical-units rule.** All physical quantities MUST be stored internally in the single canonical SI base already used by the engine ‚Äî **meters** for length/thickness, with `WaveLength` reduced to meters via its `.value` member (`Fields.fs:284`). Conversion to and from any human-facing unit (nm, ¬µm/mkm, √Ö, mm, eV, cm‚Åª¬π) MUST happen ONLY at the UI/IO boundary. No part MAY store a non-SI unit in the domain model, a project JSON payload, or a `.binz` pickle.

4. **JSON-canonical / `.binz`-derived rule.** The canonical, hand/LLM-editable project definition MUST be JSON, validated against a published JSON Schema on load. Zipped FsPickler (`.binz`, via `Softellect.Sys.Core.serialize`/`BinaryZippedFormat`, `Core.fs:257`) MUST be used ONLY for derived/bulk artefacts (sweeps, field maps, fit histories, caches) referenced as sidecars from the JSON; it MUST NOT carry the canonical project definition. No part MAY serialize the domain project model with FsPickler.

5. **FuncUI audit gate.** The Avalonia.FuncUI clone at `C:\GitHub\Avalonia.FuncUI.Clone\` MUST pass the mandatory audit (defined in ¬ßA.9) and be cleared of all flagged content BEFORE it is linked. No part MAY reference, link, or build against the clone until the audit passes. The clone's linking mechanism (local NuGet package OR project reference) is deliberately undecided and MUST remain undecided until that decision is taken later ‚Äî no part MAY resolve it.

6. **Minimum implementation.** Each part SHALL deliver the minimum that satisfies its directives. Caching, retries, added abstraction layers, config knobs, schema versioning, error-wrapping shims, backwards-compatibility shims, and migration code are OUT OF SCOPE unless a named directive in the owning part puts them in scope.

7. **Tier fidelity.** Every feature carried from 010 MUST keep its `[Core]`/`[Standard]` label. No part MAY retier, silently drop, or invent a feature absent from both 010 and the Berreman tree.

---

## Part A ‚Äî Solution architecture & cross-cutting contract (CRITICAL ‚Äî land first)

### A.0 Problem statement

The Berreman repository (`C:/GitHub/Berreman`) is a mature, type-safe F# implementation of the 4√ó4 transfer-matrix method for wave propagation through stratified, anisotropic, optionally magneto-optic/active media. Its computational core is strong: the single-system solver `OpticalSystemSolver` (`Solvers.fs:199`) already returns, for one optical system, the incident, reflected, and transmitted electromagnetic fields as an `EmFieldSystem` (`Fields.fs:550`), with R/T, Stokes, Jones-style amplitudes, ellipticity, azimuth, and in-layer fields derivable from `FieldFunctions.fs`. The gap to an "optical constructor app" is almost entirely UI, data management, materials/source libraries, design synthesis, and persistence ‚Äî not new physics, with one bounded exception for curved elements.

This Part A is the load-bearing spine. It fixes the solution/assembly layout, the orchestration domain model (the beam tree above the single-system solver), the precise engine seams every later part reuses, the storage architecture, the UI architecture, the numerical-library boundaries, and the units spine. Every later part (B‚ÄìJ) imports the contract block rather than re-deriving these. Part A defines architecture only: it states *which* types exist, *which* seams are called, and *which* invariants hold, and it does NOT specify per-feature UI panels, per-dialog layout, or per-optimizer detail ‚Äî those belong to the parts named in each directive.

The central new abstraction is the **beam tree**. A real optical system is generally not a linear chain: almost every element produces both a reflected and a transmitted beam, and the user may attach further elements to either output. The Berreman solver already yields both outputs at every element (`EmFieldSystem.reflected`/`.transmitted`, `Fields.fs:553-554`), so the net-new work is an orchestration/topology layer that routes those two outputs onward ‚Äî carrying direction, energy, and polarization (Jones/Stokes) down each branch ‚Äî and treats a mirror as the deliberate special case that carries the reflected branch only.

The one place physics extends beyond the pure 1D plane-wave formalism is curved elements (lenses, non-flat mirrors): each surface is treated as a *local* interface seen by a *local* plane wave at its local angle of incidence, with the existing 4√ó4 solver evaluated at that local angle and ray/beam propagation between elements. Part A states this contract; Part C details it.

### A.1 Solution and assembly layout

The solution MUST add five new F# projects to the existing solution file `C:/GitHub/Berreman/Berreman/Berreman.slnx` (current content verified at `Berreman.slnx:1-29`), each declared with `<Platform Project="x64" />` to match the sole `x64` configuration (`Berreman.slnx:2-4`). The build order (engine ‚Üí orchestration ‚Üí UI ‚Üí tooling) MUST be:

1. `OpticalConstructor.Domain.fsproj` ‚Äî orchestration domain: the beam-tree types (¬ßA.4), the project aggregate (¬ßA.7), the units spine (¬ßA.10). References `Berreman/Berreman.fsproj` and `Analytics/Analytics.fsproj`. MUST NOT reference any UI or storage package.
2. `OpticalConstructor.Storage.fsproj` ‚Äî JSON canonical IO, JSON-Schema validation, `.binz` sidecar IO (¬ßA.7). References `OpticalConstructor.Domain` and `Softellect.Sys`.
3. `OpticalConstructor.Optimization.fsproj` ‚Äî the library-agnostic optimization interface with ALGLIB behind it (¬ßA.8). References `OpticalConstructor.Domain` only.
4. `OpticalConstructor.Ui.fsproj` ‚Äî Avalonia + Avalonia.FuncUI (MVU), ScottPlot, WebView2-hosted Plotly.NET, OpenTK 3D viewport (¬ßA.6). References Domain, Storage, Optimization.
5. `OpticalConstructor.App.fsproj` ‚Äî the runnable entry point. References `OpticalConstructor.Ui`.

The five projects MUST sit under a new `C:/GitHub/Berreman/Berreman/OpticalConstructor/` folder, one subfolder per project. No directive in any part MAY add a sixth top-level app project; additional code MUST land in one of these five or be justified against a named directive. The existing `OpticalModel.fsproj` (a stub, `OpticalModel/Primitives.fs:9`) MUST NOT be repurposed; it MUST be left untouched.

### A.2 The engine is consumed, never forked

The new projects MUST consume the Berreman engine by project reference to `Berreman/Berreman.fsproj` and `Analytics/Analytics.fsproj` and MUST NOT copy, re-derive, or shadow any of the engine's modules. Reach-for-first primitives, by concern:

- Single-system solve ‚Üí `OpticalSystemSolver(info, system, parameters)` (`Solvers.fs:199`), returning a `Solution` (`Solvers.fs:152`) whose `.emSys` is an `EmFieldSystem` (`Solvers.fs:156`).
- Field/polarimetric outputs ‚Üí the members on `EmFieldSystem`/`Solution` in `FieldFunctions.fs` (`stokesR`/`stokesT` `FieldFunctions.fs:227,238`; `ellipticityR` `FieldFunctions.fs:157`).
- Sweeps ‚Üí `calculate`/`calculate3D` over a `RangedVariable` (`Variables.fs:237,270,42`).

No part MAY introduce a parallel solver, a parallel field model, or a parallel sweep engine.

### A.3 Domain model: optical-system and material types are reused as-is

The constructor's optical-system domain MUST be the engine's existing records and DUs, used unchanged:

- `OpticalProperties` (`MaterialProperties.fs:165`) with its `eps`/`mu`/`rho` tensors `Eps`/`Mu`/`Rho` (`MaterialProperties.fs:59,107,133`) ‚Äî the material/anisotropy model. Per-layer crystal-axis rotation is the existing `OpticalProperties.rotate` (`MaterialProperties.fs:187`) and `OpticalSystem.rotate` (`Media.fs:120`).
- `Layer` (`Media.fs:24`) with `Thickness` (`Media.fs:12`); substrate variants `Plate`/`Wedge` via `Substrate` (`Media.fs:40`) and `WedgeLayer` (`Media.fs:34`).
- `OpticalSystem` (`Media.fs:94`) ‚Äî description/upper/films/substrate/lower ‚Äî as the per-element stack; `BaseOpticalSystem` (`Media.fs:63`) and `ShortOpticalSystem` (`Media.fs:56`) as the solver feed forms; dispersive variants `OpticalPropertiesWithDisp`/`OpticalSystemWithDisp` (`Dispersion.fs:53,139`).

No part MAY define an alternate `Layer`, `OpticalSystem`, or material-tensor type. Where the UI needs a row/edit projection of a layer, that projection MUST be a view-model in `OpticalConstructor.Ui` that maps to/from `Layer` ‚Äî it MUST NOT replace `Layer` in the domain or in JSON.

### A.4 The beam-tree orchestration layer (net-new; the central new abstraction) [Core]

The solution MUST define, in `OpticalConstructor.Domain`, a beam-tree topology that sits ABOVE the single-system solver and routes its reflected/transmitted outputs along each branch. The types MUST be:

- `BeamBranch` = `Reflected | Transmitted` ‚Äî the two attachment points of a non-mirror element.
- `ConstructorElement` ‚Äî a DU classifying a placed element: `Source`, `Polarizer`, `Sample` (carrying an `OpticalSystem`, `Media.fs:94`), `Lens`, `CurvedMirror`, `FlatMirror`, `Analyzer`, `Detector`. The mirror cases (`FlatMirror`, `CurvedMirror`) are the deliberate special case: they carry the reflected branch ONLY.
- `BeamNode` ‚Äî a record carrying one `ConstructorElement`, the solver inputs needed to evaluate it (an `IncidentLightInfo`-derived local beam state: direction, energy, polarization), and its child attachments. A non-mirror node MUST expose up to two children keyed by `BeamBranch` (a branch MAY be open, terminated by a `Detector` or by nothing). A mirror node MUST expose at most one child, on `Reflected`; attaching a child on `Transmitted` to a mirror node MUST be rejected at construction time.

The orchestration MUST evaluate each node by calling the existing solver `OpticalSystemSolver` (`Solvers.fs:199`) and reading `EmFieldSystem.reflected`/`.transmitted` (`Fields.fs:553-554`) as the two outgoing beams. Propagation of an outgoing beam to the next element MUST reuse `EmField.propagate` (`BerremanMatrix.fs:224`); no part MAY re-implement plane-wave propagation. Each branch MUST carry its own beam state so that detectors on different branches report independent results (`EmFieldSystem` already isolates reflected vs transmitted, `Fields.fs:550`).

The beam tree is the orchestration aggregate; it MUST NOT embed solver internals (`BaseOpticalSystemSolver` `Solvers.fs:115` is called, not re-typed). Caching of per-node solutions, retry on solver failure, and incremental re-solve are OUT OF SCOPE for Part A; live-recalculation granularity is a Part F concern.

### A.5 Local-interface extension contract for curved elements [Core]

The solution MUST confine the one extension beyond the 1D plane-wave model to curved elements. The contract (detailed in Part C) is: a `Lens` or `CurvedMirror` element MUST be evaluated by computing a **local angle of incidence per surface** from the element's geometry (radius/curvature, aperture) and the incoming local beam direction, then calling the existing 4√ó4 solver `OpticalSystemSolver` (`Solvers.fs:199`) at that local AOI, and propagating the resulting beam to the next element via `EmField.propagate` (`BerremanMatrix.fs:224`). Part A fixes that this is the ONLY admitted extension: no part MAY introduce full 3D vector wave optics, diffraction integrals beyond the existing FFT scaffolding (`FourierTransform.fs:137`), or a second physics engine. Curved-element surface coatings MUST be modelled as the element's `OpticalSystem` films (`Media.fs:98`), not as a new coating type.

### A.6 UI architecture: Avalonia + FuncUI (MVU) + ScottPlot + WebView2/Plotly.NET + OpenTK

The UI project `OpticalConstructor.Ui` MUST be pure F# and MUST use Avalonia with Avalonia.FuncUI in the MVU/Elmish shape: a model record holding all state, a pure `update`, and a `view` that is a function of state. ScottPlot MUST provide fast native interactive 2D plots; Plotly.NET (already used by `Charting.fs:11`) MUST be retained for publication-quality/exportable charts, hosted in a WebView2 control; the 3D viewport MUST be a custom OpenTK renderer. Per P3, behaviour MUST be testable without a UI: the model/`update` MUST contain no Avalonia type.

This directive carries forward two deferred decisions VERBATIM:

> **Mandatory audit of the FuncUI clone (`C:\Github\Avalonia.FuncUI.Clone\`).** Before use, the clone **must be audited** for: **Any political statements** ‚Äî in code, comments, README/docs, license headers, resources (strings, images, icons, sample data), commit/PR/issue templates, CI config, and embedded URLs; and **Back doors or behavioral restrictions made in support of those statements** ‚Äî code that disables, degrades, nags, geofences, date-gates, or otherwise alters behavior based on locale/region/IP/name/political criteria, "protestware"-style payloads, or telephone-home/telemetry tied to any of the above. **Everything related to that must be cleared out** of the clone ‚Äî removed entirely, not merely disabled ‚Äî and the result re-reviewed to confirm nothing reintroduces it on update. This is a gating step: the clone is not approved for linking until the audit passes.

> **Linking mechanism is deliberately undecided for now.** The audited clone will be consumed **either as a local NuGet package OR as a project reference** ‚Äî that choice is made later, not now. The audit and clear-out apply identically either way. Avalonia core is consumed as the normal MIT NuGet.

No part MAY add a UI reference to the clone until the audit passes; no part MAY resolve the linking-mechanism choice.

### A.7 Storage architecture: JSON canonical + schema, `.binz` derived

The solution MUST persist the canonical project as JSON validated against a published JSON Schema on load. `OpticalConstructor.Storage` MUST:

- Define the root aggregate `OpticalConstructorProject` (systems, materials, sources, sweeps, chart settings, the beam tree of ¬ßA.4, per-element default units of ¬ßA.10) and serialize it with `System.Text.Json` + FSharp.SystemTextJson for idiomatic DU/record/option handling. Comments MUST be carried as the existing `description` field convention (`OpticalSystem.description`, `Media.fs:96`) plus an `_comment` schema field ‚Äî not as JSON comments in the canonical store.
- Validate every loaded project and every YAML rules file against the published schema using JsonSchema.Net before the model is admitted. The schema file MUST be `optical-constructor-project.schema.json` with `$defs` named `opticalSystem`, `layer`, `opticalProperties`, `beamNode`, `beamBranch`, `constructorElement`, `materialEntry`, `sourceSpec`, `unitOfMeasure`. Parts B‚ÄìJ fill these `$defs` shapes; they MUST NOT rename the anchors.
- Use zipped FsPickler ONLY for derived/bulk artefacts (sweeps, field maps, fit histories, caches), via `Softellect.Sys.Core.serialize`/`deserialize` with `BinaryZippedFormat` (`C:/GitHub/Softellect/Sys/Core.fs:254,257`) producing the `.binz` extension (`C:/GitHub/Softellect/Sys/Primitives.fs:267`). The `.binz` sidecar MUST be referenced by path from the JSON; it MUST NOT carry the canonical definition. (010 named this `Softellect.Sys.Serialization`; the in-tree module is `Softellect.Sys.Core` ‚Äî cite the real name.)
- Import external measurement/material data via FSharp.Data. Flat rules/declarations MAY use a small flat YAML subset, each file schema-validated.

Schema versioning, migration code, and backwards-compat shims for older project files are OUT OF SCOPE; the schema is published at version 1 and validated, not migrated.

### A.8 Numerical-library boundaries

The solution MUST keep linear algebra and optimization as two separate concerns, each behind its own seam.

- **Linear algebra** MUST remain the cloned Math.NET behind the existing math seam `MathNetNumericsMath` (`MathNetNumericsMath.fs:5`, whose stated purpose is to abstract a switch that is "VERY painful", `MathNetNumericsMath.fs:3-4`). Complex non-Hermitian EVD MUST stay on `MatrixEvd` (`m.Evd()`, `MatrixEvd.fs:15`) and the matrix exponential on `MatrixExp` (`MatrixExp.fs:31`). No part MAY route linear algebra through ALGLIB. `ExtremeNumericsMath` (`ExtremeNumericsMath.fs:5`) MAY remain only as a legacy reference and MUST NOT be wired into the numerics path.
- **Optimization** MUST use ALGLIB for optimization ONLY, behind a library-agnostic interface defined in `OpticalConstructor.Optimization`: a residual/objective function `(float[] -> float[])`, an optional Jacobian, parameter bounds, constraints, and a result record. ALGLIB (`minlm`, `minbleic`, `minnlc`, `minlbfgs`, `mincg`, `lsfit`) MUST sit behind that interface so physics/fitting code never depends on ALGLIB directly. The optimizer-detail (which method per workflow) belongs to Part H.

### A.9 The FuncUI clone audit is a build-gating step

The solution MUST treat the ¬ßA.6 audit as a gate: the build that links `OpticalConstructor.Ui` against the clone MUST NOT be attempted until the audit has run and the clone is cleared. This directive exists so later parts cannot accidentally introduce the reference early; it adds no new audit tooling beyond the verbatim audit of ¬ßA.6.

### A.10 Units spine: one canonical SI base, convert at the boundary

The solution MUST store every physical quantity in the canonical SI base already used by the engine and convert only at the UI/IO boundary.

- Length/thickness MUST be `double<meter>` as in `Thickness` (`Media.fs:12`) using the existing constants `nmToMeter`/`mkmToMeter`/`mmToMeter` (`Constants.fs:27,30,33`) and the `[<Measure>] meter` base (`Constants.fs:6`). Wavelength MUST be reduced to meters via `WaveLength.value` (`Fields.fs:284`).
- Each element/layer/source MUST carry its own *default* unit of measure (a `unitOfMeasure` per the schema anchor in ¬ßA.7) for display only; the stored value stays meters. This per-element default-unit plumbing is net-new and lives in `OpticalConstructor.Domain`.
- The net-new conversions MUST be eV‚Üîwavelength via `E[eV] = 1239.84 / Œª[nm]` and the spectroscopy wavenumber cm‚Åª¬π, both implemented as boundary-only conversion functions in `OpticalConstructor.Domain`. They MUST NOT be stored in the model, JSON, or `.binz`. Material-UI presentation of these units is a Part D concern.

---

## Part B ‚Äî Optical-system construction & beam-tree orchestration

### B.0 Problem statement

Part A fixed the cross-cutting contract: the canonical domain types reused from the Berreman engine (`OpticalSystem`, `Layer`, `Substrate`, `OpticalProperties`), the reused beam/field types where the reflected/transmitted split already lives (`EmFieldSystem`, `ReflectedTransmitted`, `MultipleEmFieldSystem`), the NET-NEW orchestration types (`BeamTree`/`BeamNode`/`BeamBranch`, `ConstructorElement`, `OpticalConstructorProject`), the engine seams (the 4√ó4 `OpticalSystemSolver`, the `EmField.propagate` inter-element seam), the JSON-canonical/`.binz`-derived storage rule, and the schema `$defs`. Part B builds the construction layer on top of that contract and MUST NOT re-define any of it; it cites Part A's names and the Berreman pointers verbatim.

This part owns the central act of the optical constructor: composing an end-to-end optical train from palette elements (light source ‚Üí polarizer ‚Üí sample/stack ‚Üí analyzer ‚Üí detector) and, because a real system is generally not a single linear chain, routing the reflected and transmitted outputs of every element into a branching tree of beams. The Berreman solver already produces both outputs at every element ‚Äî `OpticalSystemSolver(...).Solution.emSys` yields an `EmFieldSystem` carrying `incident`/`reflected`/`transmitted` (`Solvers.fs:199`, `Fields.fs:550`) ‚Äî so this is an orchestration/topology layer that attaches downstream sub-systems to each of those two outputs and feeds the chosen output of one element as the incident `EmField` of the next via the existing `EmField.propagate` seam (`BerremanMatrix.fs:224`). Mirrors are a deliberate special case: a mirror node carries the reflected child ONLY, by design ignoring any physically-leaked transmitted light.

This part also owns the structural editors over the reused stack types: the visual stack/layer editor that adds, deletes, reorders, duplicates and groups `Layer` rows of a `BaseOpticalSystem`/`OpticalSystem` (`Media.fs:24,63,94`); the incident & exit medium selectors that set the `upper`/`lower` `OpticalProperties` half-spaces (`Media.fs:97,100`); and the substrate-type switch between thin-film (no substrate), thick `Plate`, and `Wedge`, which routes into the engine's existing multi-reflection handling in `OpticalSystemSolver` (`Solvers.fs:201-230`). It also owns the per-element default-unit *hook* ‚Äî the field on each beam node / layer / source that records its natural display unit ‚Äî while the full unit-conversion behaviour (eV, cm‚Åª¬π, lossless round-tripping) is owned by Part D and is only referenced here.

Construction here is purely topological and structural: it assembles the reused domain records and the NET-NEW beam tree and drives the existing solver per node. Curved elements (lenses, non-flat mirrors) and the local-interface ray treatment are explicitly OUT OF SCOPE for Part B and are owned by Part C; this part only classifies a node as a mirror (reflected-only) vs. a non-mirror splitter and provides the flat-element attachment topology those parts extend. Optimization, charting, materials/dispersion editing, sources beyond the incident-light record, and persistence are owned by their respective parts and are out of scope here.

This part introduces a top-level operator surface (the construction/stack page with destructive row and branch operations), so the Operator-facing UX checklist applies and is committed in ¬ßB.10.

### B.1 Beam-tree construction MUST drive the reused single-system solver per node, never fork it

`OpticalConstructor.Domain.fsproj` MUST evaluate each `BeamNode` by calling the reused engine solver `OpticalSystemSolver(info, system, parameters)` (`Solvers.fs:199`) on that node's `OpticalSystem` and incident light, then read its `Solution.emSys` (`Solvers.fs:156`) to obtain the `EmFieldSystem` whose `reflected` and `transmitted` `EmField`s feed the node's two branches (`Fields.fs:550`). The solver, its `BaseOpticalSystemSolver` (`Solvers.fs:115`), and `SolverParameters.numberOfReflections` (`Solvers.fs:15`) MUST NOT be forked, re-derived, or shadowed (Part A constraint 2). The node's solver inputs ‚Äî `IncidentLightInfo` for a root node (`Fields.fs:338`) or an incident `EmField` produced by the parent (see ¬ßB.4) ‚Äî are stored on the `BeamNode` per Part A ¬ßA.4.

Reach-for-first primitives:
- `OpticalSystemSolver` `Solvers.fs:199` ‚Äî the only entry point for solving one element/system; returns a `Solution`.
- `Solution.emSys` `Solvers.fs:156` ‚Äî collapses `Single`/`Multiple` into one `EmFieldSystem` with `incident`/`reflected`/`transmitted`.
- `SolverParameters.defaultValue` `Solvers.fs:21` ‚Äî supplies `numberOfReflections = 3` unless a node overrides it.

Scope exclusion: Part B MUST NOT add a solver cache, a memoization layer, or a retry/error-wrapping shim around the solver; live recalculation and busy/cancel ([Standard], 010 ¬ß1) are owned by the UI part, not by the domain solver loop.

### B.2 The `BeamTree`/`BeamNode`/`BeamBranch` topology MUST be the NET-NEW orchestration carrier defined in Part A ¬ßA.4 [Core]

`OpticalConstructor.Domain.fsproj` MUST place the `BeamTree`, `BeamNode`, and `BeamBranch` definitions from Part A ¬ßA.4 in a new module `OpticalConstructor.Domain/BeamTree.fs` (new). Per Part A: `BeamBranch = Reflected | Transmitted`; a `BeamNode` carries its `ConstructorElement`, its `OpticalSystem`, its solver inputs, and up to two child attachments keyed by `BeamBranch`. This is a NET-NEW topology with no Berreman equivalent and MUST be expressed as F# records and discriminated unions (Part A constraint 1). The child attachment MUST be modelled as a `Map<BeamBranch, BeamNode>` (or equivalent immutable two-slot record), so that a non-mirror node MAY hold a `Reflected` child, a `Transmitted` child, both, or neither, and a mirror node holds at most the `Reflected` key (¬ßB.3). Immutable F# structures MUST be used throughout (Part A constraint 1; CLAUDE.md code style).

This realizes 010 ¬ß1's [Core] "Branching beam paths (reflected & transmitted) ‚Äî a system tree, not just a chain": every non-mirror element exposes two attachment points and downstream sub-systems attach to each branch independently. A linear chain (source ‚Üí polarizer ‚Üí sample ‚Üí analyzer ‚Üí detector) is the degenerate case where each node attaches a single child on the `Transmitted` branch.

Scope exclusion: no schema versioning, no migration code, and no backwards-compat shim for the tree shape; the `beamNode`/`beamBranch` `$defs` are owned by Part A ¬ßA.7 and filled field-level here (¬ßB.9), not re-versioned.

### B.3 Mirror nodes MUST carry the `Reflected` branch ONLY [Core]

`OpticalConstructor.Domain/BeamTree.fs` (new) MUST enforce that a `BeamNode` whose `ConstructorElement` is a mirror (`FlatMirror`, and ‚Äî owned by Part C ‚Äî `CurvedMirror`; the `ConstructorElement` DU is Part A ¬ßA.4) admits at most a `Reflected` child attachment and MUST reject (or structurally make unrepresentable) any `Transmitted` attachment, by design ignoring transmitted light even where it physically leaks. A smart constructor `BeamNode.attach (branch : BeamBranch) (child : BeamNode) (parent : BeamNode) : Result<BeamNode, BeamTreeError>` MUST return an error value when `branch = Transmitted` and the parent is a mirror; `Result<'T,'E>` MUST be used for this validation, not exceptions (CLAUDE.md code style). `BeamTreeError` is a NET-NEW DU defined in the same module, traced to this directive.

This realizes 010 ¬ß1's [Core] "Mirrors are a deliberate special case ‚Ä¶ the reflected branch only ‚Ä¶ Only the reflected output can carry downstream elements." Part B classifies `FlatMirror` only; the curved-mirror element and its local-interface physics are OUT OF SCOPE here and owned by Part C.

### B.4 Inter-element beam routing MUST use the reused `EmField.propagate` seam [Core]

When a `BeamNode` attaches a child on branch `b`, `OpticalConstructor.Domain/BeamTree.fs` (new) MUST take the corresponding `EmField` from the parent's solved `EmFieldSystem` ‚Äî `reflected` for `Reflected`, `transmitted` for `Transmitted` (`Fields.fs:552-554`) ‚Äî and use it as the incident field driving the child's solve, propagating it across any intervening element/gap through the reused seam `EmField.propagate (s : Layer) : EmField` (`BerremanMatrix.fs:224`). The child node MUST then be solved through the `EmField`-based path already provided by the engine: `BaseOpticalSystemSolver(emf : EmField, system : ShortOpticalSystem)` (`Solvers.fs:149`), where `ShortOpticalSystem` (`Media.fs:56`) carries the child's `films` and `lower`. The energy/polarization carried along the branch is exactly the field state inside the propagated `EmField` (its `emComponents`, `Fields.fs:427`); Part B MUST NOT introduce a separate Jones/Stokes accumulator ‚Äî Stokes/ellipticity/azimuth read-outs are computed by the field-function seam owned elsewhere (Part A engine seams, `FieldFunctions.fs`).

Reach-for-first primitives:
- `EmField.propagate` `BerremanMatrix.fs:224` ‚Äî the single inter-element propagation seam; advances an `EmField` across a `Layer`.
- `BaseOpticalSystemSolver(emf, system)` `Solvers.fs:149` ‚Äî the `EmField`-driven solver overload for a downstream node.
- `ShortOpticalSystem` `Media.fs:56` ‚Äî the films-plus-lower system a downstream `EmField` is solved against.

Scope exclusion: Part B routes flat-element beams along the boundary normal only; off-axis ray direction, focusing, and beam-waist propagation are OUT OF SCOPE (owned by Part C). No incoherent-layer averaging here ([Standard], 010 ¬ß3, owned by the sources part).

### B.5 The visual stack/layer editor MUST operate on the reused `Layer`/`OpticalSystem` records [Core]

`OpticalConstructor.Ui.fsproj` MUST provide a stack/layer editor whose rows are the reused `Layer` records of a node's `OpticalSystem.films : List<Layer>` (`Media.fs:98`), each row editing that layer's `thickness : Thickness` (`Media.fs:12`) and `properties : OpticalProperties` (`Media.fs:26`, the tensor record `MaterialProperties.fs:165`). The editor MUST support add, delete, reorder, duplicate, and group operations as pure transformations producing a new `films` list (immutable; Part A constraint 1), and the surrounding `OpticalSystem` MUST be rebuilt via record copy-and-update ‚Äî never by mutating engine state. Layer-class/anisotropy and crystal-axis rotation controls ([Standard], 010 ¬ß1) MUST reuse the engine's `Layer.rotate` / `OpticalSystem.rotate` members (`Media.fs:30`, `Media.fs:120`) rather than re-deriving rotations.

Reach-for-first primitives:
- `OpticalSystem.films` `Media.fs:98` ‚Äî the reused list the editor rows map to.
- `Thickness` DU `Media.fs:12` ‚Äî the per-row thickness value (`Thickness of double<meter> | Infinity`); thickness is stored in meters (Part A canonical-units rule).
- `OpticalSystem.rotate` / `Layer.rotate` `Media.fs:120,30` ‚Äî reuse for the [Standard] orientation controls; do not re-implement Euler rotation.

This realizes 010 ¬ß1's [Core] "Visual stack/layer editor ‚Äî add, delete, reorder, duplicate, and group layers ‚Ä¶ edit thickness and material per row." The [Standard] repeat/period builder (010 ¬ß1) is NOT delivered by Part B; it is owned by Part J (¬ßJ.2).

### B.6 Incident & exit medium selectors MUST set the reused `upper`/`lower` half-spaces [Core]

`OpticalConstructor.Ui.fsproj` MUST provide incident- and exit-medium selectors that set, respectively, the `OpticalSystem.upper` and `OpticalSystem.lower` `OpticalProperties` half-spaces of the edited system (`Media.fs:97,100`). Each selector MUST resolve to an `OpticalProperties` value (the reused tensor record, `MaterialProperties.fs:165`) either by refractive-index entry or by reference to a materials-library entry; the materials library and dispersion resolution are owned by other parts, so Part B MUST consume a resolved `OpticalProperties` and MUST NOT re-implement index‚Üítensor construction. Setting a selector MUST produce a new `OpticalSystem` by record update, preserving `films` and `substrate`.

This realizes 010 ¬ß1's [Core] "Incident & exit medium selectors (upper/lower half-spaces) with refractive index or material reference."

### B.7 The substrate-type switch MUST toggle the reused `Substrate` DU and route into existing multi-reflection handling [Core]

`OpticalConstructor.Ui.fsproj` MUST provide a substrate-type switch with exactly three states ‚Äî thin film, thick plate, wedge ‚Äî that sets `OpticalSystem.substrate : Substrate option` (`Media.fs:99`): thin film ‚áí `None`; plate ‚áí `Some (Plate layer)`; wedge ‚áí `Some (Wedge wedgeLayer)` exposing the `WedgeAngle` (`Media.fs:34,40`, `Fields.fs:328`). The switch MUST NOT change how multiple internal reflections are computed: that behaviour is already implemented in `OpticalSystemSolver` (`Solvers.fs:201-230`), which branches on `system.substrate` and, for `Plate`/`Wedge`, iterates the reflected/transmitted steps using `EmField.propagate` (`Solvers.fs:209,222`); Part B MUST route into that existing path unchanged and MUST NOT fork it.

Reach-for-first primitives:
- `Substrate` DU `Media.fs:40` (`Plate of Layer | Wedge of WedgeLayer`) ‚Äî the reused carrier the switch toggles.
- `OpticalSystem.substrate` `Media.fs:99` ‚Äî the `option` field set by the switch.
- `OpticalSystemSolver` substrate branch `Solvers.fs:201-230` ‚Äî the existing multi-reflection driver; reuse, do not reimplement.

This realizes 010 ¬ß1's [Core] "Substrate type switch: thin film vs. thick plate vs. wedge (with wedge angle), exposing the existing multi-reflection handling."

### B.8 Each beam node, layer, and source MUST carry a per-element default-unit hook [Core]

`OpticalConstructor.Domain/BeamTree.fs` (new) and the `OpticalConstructorProject` aggregate (Part A ¬ßA.7) MUST attach a per-element default-unit field ‚Äî a `UnitOfMeasure` value (the NET-NEW DU owned by Part D; schema `$def` `unitOfMeasure`, Part A ¬ßA.7) ‚Äî to each `BeamNode`, each editor layer row, and each source/incident-light entry, recording the unit that element was created in / is most natural for it. Part B owns ONLY this hook: storing and surfacing the default unit so the editor can display a plate in mm, a film in nm, and a source in nm/¬µm/eV without the user converting by hand. The conversion behaviour itself ‚Äî meters‚Üînm/¬µm/√Ö/mm, eV via `E[eV] = 1239.84 / Œª[nm]`, cm‚Åª¬π ‚Äî is owned by Part D and MUST NOT be implemented in Part B. Per Part A's canonical-units rule (constraint 3), the underlying physical quantities MUST remain stored in meters (`double<meter>`, `Constants.fs:6`; `WaveLength.value`, `Fields.fs:284`); the default-unit hook is display metadata only and MUST NOT change any stored SI value.

This realizes 010 ¬ß1's [Core] "Per-element default unit of measure ‚Äî each layer/element/source remembers and displays the unit natural to it ‚Ä¶ full unit behaviour in ¬ß2" (Part D).

### B.9 The beam tree and constructed systems MUST serialize to the JSON-canonical project, never to `.binz`

`OpticalConstructor.Storage.fsproj` MUST serialize the `BeamTree`, its `BeamNode`s, their `OpticalSystem`s, and the per-element default-unit hooks into the JSON-canonical `OpticalConstructorProject` validated against `optical-constructor-project.schema.json` (Part A ¬ßA.7), filling the field-level shapes of the `beamNode`, `beamBranch`, `opticalSystem`, `layer`, and `unitOfMeasure` `$defs` (owned by Part A). FSharp.SystemTextJson MUST be used for DU/record/option serialization (Part A storage seam). The domain project model ‚Äî including the beam tree ‚Äî MUST NOT be serialized with FsPickler/`.binz` (Part A constraint 4); `.binz` via `Softellect.Sys.Core.serialize`/`BinaryZippedFormat` (`C:/GitHub/Softellect/Sys/Core.fs:254,257`) is reserved for derived/bulk sidecars and is out of scope for Part B. Thicknesses and wavelengths in the JSON MUST be the canonical SI values (meters), with human units applied only at the UI/IO boundary (Part A constraint 3).

Scope exclusion: schema versioning, autosave, recent-files, and undo/redo persistence ([Standard], 010 ¬ß7) are out of scope for Part B; only the field-level shapes of the listed `$defs` are filled here.

### B.10 The construction page MUST commit the operator-facing UX for destructive structural edits

`OpticalConstructor.Ui.fsproj` introduces the top-level construction/stack-and-tree page with destructive operations (delete layer, delete branch/sub-tree, detach mirror reflected child), so it MUST commit explicitly on the operator UX checklist:

1. **Discoverability/nav entry.** The construction page MUST be a top-level navigation entry in the main shell, reachable without opening a dialog, and MUST be the default landing surface for a newly opened or newly created project.
2. **Progress granularity.** Per-node solve invoked from this page (¬ßB.1) MUST surface a busy indicator at node granularity; because a single flat-element solve is short, the page MUST NOT block the whole tree while one node recomputes. Long sweeps/optimizations are owned by other parts and are out of scope here.
3. **Pre-confirmation gate vs one-click.** Deleting a layer row MUST be one-click with undo (item 5); deleting a beam node that has attached children (a sub-tree) MUST present a pre-confirmation gate naming the count of descendant nodes that will be removed, re-derived live from the tree (no stale count).
4. **Completion‚Üíresults refresh.** After any structural edit (add/delete/reorder/duplicate/group a layer, attach/detach a branch, toggle substrate, change a medium), the affected sub-tree MUST be re-solved and the dependent schematic/results views MUST refresh from the new `EmFieldSystem` (¬ßB.1) without a manual reload.
5. **Opposing-action UX + undo.** Every destructive structural action (delete, detach) MUST have an opposing add/attach action in the same toolbar, and a single-level undo MUST restore the immediately prior immutable tree/`films` snapshot (the model is immutable per ¬ßB.2/¬ßB.5, so undo is a prior-value swap, not a mutation reversal). Multi-level undo/redo history ([Standard], 010 ¬ß7) is owned by Part I (¬ßI.6).
6. **Committable file vs root `.gitignore`.** The JSON project file written by ¬ßB.9 is a committable user artefact and MUST default to the project's working folder, not the repository root; Part B MUST NOT write derived `.binz` sidecars from the construction page (those are out of scope here, ¬ßB.9).

### B.11 Gradient-index / inhomogeneous layers MUST auto-discretize into reused `Layer` sub-layers [Standard]

`OpticalConstructor.Domain/BeamTree.fs` (new) MUST realise 010 ¬ß1's [Standard] "Gradient-index / inhomogeneous layers auto-discretized into sub-layers" (010 lines 123-124) as a pure expansion that turns one continuously-varying-index layer into an ordered list of homogeneous reused `Layer` records (`Media.fs:24`). This part MUST add a net-new record `GradientLayer = { totalThickness : double<meter>; subLayerCount : int; indexProfile : double<meter> -> OpticalProperties }` and a pure function `discretize : GradientLayer -> Layer list` that slices `totalThickness` into `subLayerCount` equal `Thickness.Thickness` sub-layers (`Media.fs:12`), each carrying the `OpticalProperties` (`MaterialProperties.fs:165`) sampled from `indexProfile` at that sub-layer's mid-depth. The produced sub-layers MUST be ordinary `Layer` records indistinguishable from manually entered ones ‚Äî exactly the flat-`Layer`-list discipline `RepeatBuilder.expand` follows (Part J ¬ßJ.2) ‚Äî and MUST be assignable straight into `OpticalSystem.films` (`Media.fs:98`); this part MUST NOT introduce a new gradient-layer engine type, MUST NOT discretize at solve time inside the solver, and MUST NOT store the unfactored profile in the canonical JSON (only the expanded `films` persist, per ¬ßB.9). `subLayerCount` MUST be a required argument validated `>= 1` through the Part J ¬ßJ.9 validation seam; thicknesses MUST remain `double<meter>` (Part A canonical-units rule). Adaptive/error-driven sub-layer refinement is OUT OF SCOPE ‚Äî the count is caller-supplied, uniform slicing only.

