## Part C ‚Äî Lenses & non-flat (curved) mirror elements

### C.0 Problem statement

The Berreman engine is a strict 1D plane-wave transfer-matrix formalism: every interface it understands is a flat, infinite plane, and a single incidence angle (`IncidenceAngle`, `Fields.fs:22`) describes the whole wave. A lens or a concave/convex mirror has no place in that model as-is, because its surface is curved ‚Äî the angle between the incoming ray and the local surface normal varies continuously from the optical axis out to the aperture edge. Without focusing elements a plane wave can never be turned into a converging or diverging beam, so this gap is squarely [Core] (010 ¬ß1, line 86). The preliminary spec's "Engine note for curved elements" (010 lines 43-48) states the only admissible resolution: treat each curved surface as a finite set of *local* flat interfaces, each seen by a *local* plane wave carrying its own direction, and evaluate the existing 4√ó4 solver at each local angle of incidence; ray/beam geometry between elements carries the beam from one element to the next.

This part defines the curved-element domain model and the local-interface evaluation that turns one curved surface into many solver runs. It is a NET-NEW orchestration concern: a tree-wide Grep of the Berreman tree for `lens|curv|spheric|aperture|radius|focal|mirror|graded` returns no engine type, so nothing here forks or shadows an engine primitive. The work is confined to `OpticalConstructor.Domain.fsproj` (Part A assembly list) and consumes three engine seams unchanged: the per-system solver `OpticalSystemSolver` (`Solvers.fs:199`), the local-angle shift `IncidentLightInfo.rotateY` (`Fields.fs:411`), and the inter-element propagator `EmField.propagate` (`BerremanMatrix.fs:224`, the seam Part A names ¬ßA "Beam / field types"). A curved surface becomes a `ConstructorElement.Lens` or `ConstructorElement.CurvedMirror` (Part A ¬ßA.4 DU) whose evaluation is a fan of `BeamNode`s on the Part A `BeamTree` (Part A ¬ßA.4), one per sampled aperture zone.

The element's *coating* is the place where the existing engine is reused most directly: a coating on a curved surface is an ordinary `OpticalSystem` (`Media.fs:94`) ‚Äî upper medium, a `films` stack of `Layer`s (`Media.fs:24`), a `Substrate` (`Media.fs:40`), lower medium ‚Äî and the substrate material/aperture/curvature are metadata wrapped around it. The only physics that differs zone-to-zone is the local AOI and, for EUV, the multilayer *period*: a depth-graded mirror scales its bilayer spacing across the aperture (~5% center-to-edge, 010 line 92) so that reflectance stays uniform as the local angle sweeps. Grading is therefore a per-zone rescale of the coating's `Layer.thickness` (`Media.fs:12`) values, computed at the IO/orchestration boundary, never a new layer type and never a stored non-SI quantity (Part A canonical-units rule).

Scope is the curved-element domain model, its decomposition into local flat interfaces, the per-zone local-AOI solver fan, coating attachment on curved surfaces, and EUV depth-graded period scaling. Wavefront diffraction, full Gaussian-beam physics beyond the existing FFT scaffolding (`FourierTransform.fs:74`), aberration ray tracing through glass volumes, image formation, automatic aperture-sampling refinement, caching of zone solves, retries, and any background-job UX are OUT OF SCOPE for this part; the per-zone solves are driven synchronously by the same orchestration that drives a flat element. This part introduces no top-level operator page, no long-running background job, and no destructive action, so the operator-facing UX checklist does not apply.

### C.1 Define the curved-surface geometry record in the Domain project

This part MUST add a `CurvedSurface` record to a new file `OpticalConstructor/Domain/CurvedElements.fs` inside `OpticalConstructor.Domain.fsproj` (Part A assembly list). The record MUST carry: `radiusOfCurvature : double<meter>` (signed ‚Äî negative concave, positive convex, by the sign convention fixed in C.4), `semiAperture : double<meter>` (the clear half-aperture radius), `figure : SurfaceFigure`, and `coating : OpticalSystem` (`Media.fs:94`). All lengths MUST be stored in meters via the engine measure `[<Measure>] meter` (`Constants.fs:6`), satisfying the Part A canonical-units rule; nm/¬µm/mm entry MUST be converted at the UI boundary only, using `nmToMeter`/`mkmToMeter`/`mmToMeter` (`Constants.fs:27,30,33`). The record MUST NOT introduce its own thickness or wavelength representation ‚Äî thickness lives on the coating's `Layer`s (`Media.fs:12`), wavelength on the source via `WaveLength.value` (`Fields.fs:284`).

### C.2 Define the `SurfaceFigure` discriminated union for spherical and aspheric profiles

This part MUST add a `SurfaceFigure` DU to `OpticalConstructor/Domain/CurvedElements.fs` with exactly two cases for the committed scope: `Spherical` (curvature fully described by `CurvedSurface.radiusOfCurvature`) and `Aspheric of conic : double * evenPolynomial : double<meter> list` (conic constant plus even asphere polynomial coefficients), matching 010's "spherical/aspheric lenses" ([Core], 010 line 88). The sag function `z(r)` MUST be implemented as a pure F# function `sag : SurfaceFigure -> double<meter> -> double<meter> -> double<meter>` (figure, radius-of-curvature, radial position) returning the surface height; for `Spherical` it MUST be the exact spherical sag, for `Aspheric` the conic-plus-polynomial sag. No further figure cases (toroidal, freeform, diffractive) MAY be added ‚Äî they are absent from 010 and excluded here.

### C.3 Decompose a curved surface into local flat interfaces sampled across the aperture

This part MUST add `sampleZones : CurvedSurface -> int -> LocalZone list` to `OpticalConstructor/Domain/CurvedElements.fs`, where the `int` is the zone count supplied by the caller and `LocalZone` is a record carrying the zone's radial position `radialPosition : double<meter>`, its `localAoiShift : Angle` (the angle between the chord normal at that radius and the optical axis, derived from `SurfaceFigure.sag` per C.2), and its `coating : OpticalSystem`. Sampling MUST be uniform in aperture radius from axis (`radialPosition = 0`) to `semiAperture`. The function MUST NOT perform adaptive refinement, MUST NOT cache, and MUST NOT default the zone count ‚Äî the count is a required argument owned by the orchestration caller (Part F/G consumers of `BeamTree`). `Angle` MUST be the engine type used by `IncidenceAngle` (`Fields.fs:22`, via `Geometry.Angle`), so that C.5 can feed the shift straight into `IncidentLightInfo.rotateY` (`Fields.fs:411`).

### C.4 Fix the signed radius-of-curvature convention for concave vs. convex elements

This part MUST document and enforce, in `OpticalConstructor/Domain/CurvedElements.fs` as an XML-doc comment on `CurvedSurface.radiusOfCurvature` and as the body of `sag` (C.2), the single sign convention: a surface whose center of curvature lies on the *incoming-light* side (concave toward the source) MUST have negative `radiusOfCurvature`, and convex MUST be positive. This is the only convention; there is NO per-element override flag and NO "convention selector" config knob. A concave mirror (`ConstructorElement.CurvedMirror`, Part A ¬ßA.4) and a convex mirror are distinguished solely by this sign. Both lens-surface curvatures of a biconvex/meniscus lens MUST be represented as two `CurvedSurface` records (one per physical surface), not as a single two-radius record, so that each surface is one local-interface evaluation.

### C.5 Evaluate each zone through the engine 4√ó4 solver at its local angle of incidence

This part MUST add `solveZone : IncidentLightInfo -> LocalZone -> SolverParameters -> Solution` to `OpticalConstructor/Domain/CurvedElements.fs`. For each `LocalZone` (C.3) it MUST: (1) form the local incident light by applying the zone's `localAoiShift` to the incoming `IncidentLightInfo` via `IncidentLightInfo.rotateY` (`Fields.fs:411`, which adds the angle onto `incidenceAngle`); (2) run the engine's per-system solver `OpticalSystemSolver(localInfo, zone.coating, parameters)` (`Solvers.fs:199`) to obtain the reflected and transmitted fields. The `SolverParameters` (`Solvers.fs:15`) MUST be passed through unchanged ‚Äî the curved-element path MUST NOT invent its own reflection-count or thresholds. This part MUST NOT re-implement reflectance/transmittance; the `Solution.emSys` reflected/transmitted split (`Solvers.fs:156`) is the output, consumed downstream exactly as a flat element's output is.

### C.6 Build the per-zone beam fan onto the Part A `BeamTree`, honoring the mirror special case

This part MUST add `attachCurvedElement : ConstructorElement -> BeamNode -> BeamNode` to `OpticalConstructor/Domain/CurvedElements.fs`, producing, for a `Lens` or `CurvedMirror`, the fan of child `BeamNode`s (Part A ¬ßA.4) ‚Äî one node per `LocalZone` solve from C.5. For `ConstructorElement.Lens` each zone node MUST expose both `BeamBranch.Reflected` and `BeamBranch.Transmitted` attachments (Part A ¬ßA.4). For `ConstructorElement.CurvedMirror` each zone node MUST expose the `BeamBranch.Reflected` attachment ONLY and MUST drop the transmitted field, matching the deliberate mirror special case (010 lines 78-80; Part A ¬ßA.4 "a mirror `BeamNode` carries the `Reflected` child ONLY"). This part MUST NOT redefine `BeamTree`, `BeamNode`, `BeamBranch`, or `ConstructorElement` ‚Äî they are owned by Part A ¬ßA.4 and imported here.

### C.7 Propagate the beam between curved elements using the engine propagator

This part MUST carry the beam from one curved element's zone output to the next element using the engine inter-element propagator `EmField.propagate (s : Layer)` (`BerremanMatrix.fs:224`, the seam Part A names under "Beam / field types"), wrapping the inter-element gap as a `Layer` (`Media.fs:24`) whose `thickness` (`Media.fs:12`) is the axial separation in meters and whose `properties` are the gap medium's `OpticalProperties` (`MaterialProperties.fs:165`). This part MUST NOT add a second propagation routine or a ray-transfer (ABCD) matrix module; the focusing geometry needed for the committed [Core] scope is the per-zone local-AOI fan (C.3, C.5) plus this axial propagation. Full Gaussian-beam waist/divergence propagation remains the existing FFT scaffolding `createGaussian`/`FourierTransform` (`FourierTransform.fs:74,137`) and is OUT OF SCOPE for this part.

### C.8 Attach coatings on curved surfaces as ordinary engine optical systems

This part MUST represent a coating on a curved surface as the `OpticalSystem` stored in `CurvedSurface.coating` (C.1), reusing `OpticalSystem` (`Media.fs:94`), its `films : Layer list` (`Media.fs:98`), and `Substrate` (`Plate | Wedge`, `Media.fs:40`) verbatim ‚Äî the substrate material of the lens/mirror IS the coating system's `lower`/`substrate`. This part MUST NOT define a curved-specific layer or coating type. The same coating `OpticalSystem` MUST be shared by every `LocalZone` (C.3) except where C.9 rescales its layer thicknesses for grading; sharing MUST be by value (immutable record reuse), consistent with the Part A immutability commitment and CLAUDE.md immutable-structures rule.

### C.9 Apply EUV depth-graded multilayer spacing as a per-zone thickness rescale [Core]

This part MUST add `gradeCoating : CurvedSurface -> LocalZone -> OpticalSystem` to `OpticalConstructor/Domain/CurvedElements.fs`, which, for a depth-graded EUV multilayer mirror, returns the zone's coating with every `Layer.thickness` (`Media.fs:12`) of the bilayer stack scaled by a factor that varies with the zone's `radialPosition` (C.3) so the multilayer period changes across the aperture (~5% center-to-edge, 010 line 92, [Core]). The scaling factor MUST be computed from the zone's `localAoiShift` and applied only to `Thickness.Thickness d` cases (`Media.fs:12`), leaving `Thickness.Infinity` untouched. All scaled thicknesses MUST remain in `double<meter>` (`Constants.fs:6`); the ~5% figure is a default that MUST be expressed as a meter-valued scale, never stored in a non-SI unit (Part A canonical-units rule). Grading MUST be opt-in per element (a flag on the `ConstructorElement.CurvedMirror`/`Lens` payload, Part A ¬ßA.4); a non-graded element MUST reuse the single shared coating from C.8 with no rescale. This part MUST NOT add a new graded-layer type, a period-versus-radius config table, or schema versioning for grading.

### C.10 Convert and validate curved-element units only at the IO/UI boundary

This part MUST keep all `CurvedSurface`/`LocalZone` fields in canonical SI (meters, engine `Angle`) inside the domain, and MUST place radius/aperture/sag unit conversion (nm/¬µm/mm/√Ö ‚Üî meter) in the UI/Storage layer using `nmToMeter`/`mkmToMeter`/`mmToMeter` (`Constants.fs:27,30,33`), satisfying the Part A JSON-canonical rule. The curved-element fields added by this part MUST serialize through the JSON-canonical project model under the Part A `constructorElement` schema `$def` (Part A ¬ßA.7); they MUST NOT be FsPickler-serialized into the canonical project (Part A `.binz`-derived rule). Per-zone solver outputs, being derived bulk results, MAY be written to a `.binz` sidecar via `Softellect.Sys.Core.serialize` with `BinaryZippedFormat` (`Core.fs:257`) when a sweep persists them, but this part adds no such sidecar itself.

---

## Part D ‚Äî Optical substances / materials management & units of measure

### D.0 Problem statement

The Berreman engine already carries everything needed to *evaluate* a material once its tensors are known: `OpticalProperties` (eps/mu/rho 3√ó3 tensors) is `MaterialProperties.fs:165`, the per-component DUs `Eps`/`Mu`/`Rho`/`RhoT` are `MaterialProperties.fs:59,107,133,153`, and the dispersion abstraction `OpticalPropertiesWithDisp` (`Dispersion.fs:53`) wraps wavelength-dependent tensors as `WaveLength -> Eps/Mu/Rho` closures (`Dispersion.fs:9,24,38`). Two concrete dispersive materials already exist as worked references ‚Äî `Silicon` and `Langasite` (`OpticalProperties/Dispersive.fs:74,19`) ‚Äî both built by hand-coding closures over `w.value` (`Fields.fs:284`). What is missing, per 010 Part II ¬ß2, is the *management layer*: a searchable materials library, a reusable analytic-model catalogue (Sellmeier/Cauchy/Lorentz/Drude/Tauc-Lorentz/‚Ä¶), refractiveindex.info + CSV import/export, and the per-element default-unit plumbing with net-new eV and cm‚Åª¬π photon-energy conversions. This part owns that layer.

The canonical-units rule (¬ß0 constraint 3) is the spine of this part. Every material datum and every dispersion-model coefficient that is a physical length or energy MUST be stored internally in the single SI base the engine already uses ‚Äî meters via `WaveLength.value` (`Fields.fs:284`), reusing the conversion constants `nmToMeter`/`mkmToMeter`/`mmToMeter` (`Constants.fs:27,30,33`). The engine has no √Öngstr√∂m, no eV and no cm‚Åª¬π measure today; those are net-new and live ONLY at the UI/IO boundary. eV converts by `E[eV] = 1239.84 / Œª[nm]` and wavenumber by `ŒΩÃÉ[cm‚Åª¬π] = 1e7 / Œª[nm]`. A material parsed from a refractiveindex.info YAML page expressed in ¬µm or a CSV column in nm MUST be reduced to a meter-based `WaveLength` before any tensor is built, and a coefficient set entered as "Sellmeier in ¬µm¬≤" MUST be normalised so the resulting closure consumes a meter-based `WaveLength` and returns the same `Eps` the engine would compute by hand.

The dispersion-model catalogue is the second deliverable. 010 ¬ß2 names a fixed set of analytic forms; this part defines each as a pure F# function `WaveLength -> ComplexRefractionIndex` (reusing `ComplexRefractionIndex`, `MaterialProperties.fs:43`), composed into an `EpsWithDisp` closure exactly as `Silicon` does (`OpticalProperties/Dispersive.fs:88,92`). The catalogue is data-driven ‚Äî a coefficient record per model ‚Äî so the UI editor and the JSON schema describe coefficients, not code. Anisotropic entries reuse the existing three-index constructor `Eps.fromComplexRefractionIndex (n1, n2, n3)` (`MaterialProperties.fs:87`) so that n_o/n_e (uniaxial) and n_x/n_y/n_z (biaxial) flow straight into the engine's tensor model with no new tensor algebra; crystal-axis orientation reuses `Layer.rotate` (`Media.fs:30`) and is NOT redefined here.

The material-preview plots are the third deliverable, and they are almost entirely plumbing: the engine already exposes `plotN11`/`plotXi11`/`plotRho11` and siblings (`Analytics/Charting.fs:95,96,105`) that consume an `OpticalPropertiesWithDisp` and a `Range<WaveLength>` (`Variables.fs:22`). This part routes a library entry's `OpticalPropertiesWithDisp` into those functions and adds the spectral-axis unit toggle (nm / ¬µm / √Ö / eV / cm‚Åª¬π) at the chart boundary. The [Standard] thermo-optic dn/dT (temperature/composition dependence) deliverable is owned by this part and specified in D.12. Caching of evaluated dispersion curves, model-coefficient schema versioning, retry/back-off on import, and migration of legacy material files are OUT OF SCOPE for this part; only the features named in the directives below are in scope, each at its 010 tier.

This part introduces no top-level operator page, no long-running background job, and no destructive action (import is additive into an in-memory library, preview is read-only); the operator-facing UX checklist is therefore not triggered and is skipped. The new code lives in `OpticalConstructor.Domain.fsproj` (units, models, library aggregate) and `OpticalConstructor.Storage.fsproj` (YAML/CSV import-export), both defined in Part A's project layout; the preview-plot routing lives in `OpticalConstructor.Ui.fsproj`. No part of this work forks the engine, and no domain payload stores a non-SI unit.

### D.1 Define the boundary unit-of-measure vocabulary as a net-new DU [Core]

This part MUST add a new module `Units.fs` in `OpticalConstructor.Domain.fsproj` defining a discriminated union `UnitOfMeasure` enumerating exactly the human-facing units 010 ¬ß2 names: `Meter | Millimeter | Micrometer | Nanometer | Angstrom | ElectronVolt | Wavenumber`. This DU is the ONLY place a non-SI unit name appears in the solution; it is a UI/IO label, never a storage type. The module MUST NOT introduce new F# `[<Measure>]` types for √Ö, eV, or cm‚Åª¬π that shadow `Constants.fs` ‚Äî length units reduce through the existing measures `nm`/`mkm`/`mm`/`meter` (`Constants.fs:6,10,13,17`); √Ö, eV and cm‚Åª¬π are handled by the scalar conversions in D.2. The DU MUST be the F# realisation of the `unitOfMeasure` `$def` Part A reserves in `optical-constructor-project.schema.json` (¬ßA.7); this part fills that `$def` as a string `enum` of the seven member names and MUST NOT add members absent from 010 ¬ß2.

### D.2 Implement boundary length-and-energy conversions reusing engine constants [Core]

`Units.fs` MUST provide two total functions, `toMeters : UnitOfMeasure -> float -> float<meter>` and `toWaveLength : UnitOfMeasure -> float -> WaveLength`, that convert a human-entered scalar into the engine's canonical base. For `Meter`/`Millimeter`/`Micrometer`/`Nanometer` the implementation MUST multiply by the existing constants `mmToMeter`/`mkmToMeter`/`nmToMeter` (`Constants.fs:27,30,33`) and MUST NOT re-derive those factors. For `Angstrom` the factor MUST be `1.0e-10<meter>` per √Ö. For `ElectronVolt` the function MUST first map energy to wavelength by `Œª[nm] = 1239.84 / E[eV]` then through `nmToMeter`; for `Wavenumber` it MUST map `Œª[nm] = 1.0e7 / ŒΩÃÉ[cm‚Åª¬π]` then through `nmToMeter`. The literal `1239.84` MUST appear exactly once, as a named binding `let evNmProduct = 1239.84` carrying a doc-comment citing `E[eV] = 1239.84 / Œª[nm]`. The inverse functions `fromMeters : UnitOfMeasure -> float<meter> -> float` and `wavelengthToUnit : UnitOfMeasure -> WaveLength -> float` MUST be provided for display, dividing by the same constants and inverting the eV/cm‚Åª¬π relations; `wavelengthToUnit` MUST read the canonical value via `WaveLength.value` (`Fields.fs:284`). These functions are the SOLE conversion seam ‚Äî no other module in the solution MAY hand-roll a unit conversion.

### D.3 Reuse `WaveLength` at the engine boundary; do not fork it [Core]

When a converted value re-enters the engine it MUST be carried as the engine's `WaveLength` DU (`Fields.fs:280`), constructed via its `Nm`/`Mkm` cases or `WaveLength.nm`/`WaveLength.mkm` (`Fields.fs:294,295`). `toWaveLength Nanometer` and `toWaveLength Micrometer` MUST return `Nm`/`Mkm` respectively so the engine's own `.value` reduction (`Fields.fs:286,287`) performs the final SI step; for `Angstrom`, `ElectronVolt` and `Wavenumber` ‚Äî which `WaveLength` cannot represent natively ‚Äî `toWaveLength` MUST first reduce to nm (D.2) and return `Nm`. This part MUST NOT add `Angstrom`/`Ev`/`Wavenumber` cases to the engine's `WaveLength` DU; the boundary DU `UnitOfMeasure` (D.1) is the place those live, and the engine continues to see only `Mkm`/`Nm`.

### D.4 Attach a per-element default unit to project elements via Part A's aggregate [Core]

This part MUST define a record `defaultUnit : UnitOfMeasure` field carried on each unit-bearing project element (layer/element/source) inside the `OpticalConstructorProject` aggregate Part A owns (¬ßA.7). This part does NOT redefine that aggregate; it specifies that the per-element default-unit value uses the D.1 DU and is the value rendered/edited in the UI and persisted in JSON. The default-unit value is metadata about *display only*: it MUST NOT influence the stored canonical SI value, and round-tripping a project through JSON MUST preserve both the canonical SI datum and its `defaultUnit` label independently. The schema `$def` `unitOfMeasure` (¬ßA.7) is the JSON shape; the per-element placement (which records carry a `defaultUnit`) is fixed by Part B (stack/layer) and Part E (sources) and MUST NOT be re-specified here beyond the requirement that the carried type is `UnitOfMeasure`.

### D.5 Define the dispersion-model coefficient catalogue as data, not code [Core]

This part MUST add a module `DispersionModels.fs` in `OpticalConstructor.Domain.fsproj` defining one F# record per analytic model named in 010 ¬ß2 ‚Äî `Sellmeier`, `Cauchy`, `Lorentz` (Drude‚ÄìLorentz), `Drude`, `TaucLorentz`, `GaussianOscillator`, and `ConstantNK` (constant n+ik) ‚Äî each holding ONLY its coefficient scalars (e.g. Sellmeier `b` and `c` term lists; Cauchy `a`,`b`,`c`; Drude plasma/damping frequencies; constant `n`,`k`). A wrapping DU `DispersionModel` MUST enumerate these records so the editor and schema can describe a single tagged choice. Each record MUST carry an explicit `wavelengthUnit : UnitOfMeasure` (D.1) naming the unit its coefficients were tabulated in (Sellmeier `c` terms are conventionally ¬µm¬≤), so evaluation (D.6) can normalise to the engine's meter base. This catalogue MUST be the realisation of the schema `$def` `materialEntry` dispersion sub-object (¬ßA.7); coefficient field shapes are owned here. Schema versioning of these coefficient records is OUT OF SCOPE.

### D.6 Evaluate each model to an `OpticalPropertiesWithDisp` reusing the engine's closure shape [Core]

`DispersionModels.fs` MUST provide `evaluate : DispersionModel -> (WaveLength -> ComplexRefractionIndex)`, returning a closure of exactly the shape `Silicon`/`Langasite` build by hand (`OpticalProperties/Dispersive.fs:87,52`). The closure MUST read the canonical wavelength via `WaveLength.value` (`Fields.fs:284`), normalise it against the record's `wavelengthUnit` (D.5) using D.2, apply the analytic formula, and return a `ComplexRefractionIndex` (`MaterialProperties.fs:43`). A second function `toOpticalProperties : DispersionModel -> OpticalPropertiesWithDisp` MUST compose that closure into an `EpsWithDisp` via `Eps.fromComplexRefractionIndex` (`MaterialProperties.fs:87`) wrapped as `EpsWithDisp` (the `EpsWithDisp` case of the `EpsWithDisp` DU, `Dispersion.fs:9-10`), with `muWithDisp = Mu.vacuum.dispersive` and `rhoWithDisp = Rho.vacuum.dispersive` for isotropic entries ‚Äî mirroring `Silicon`'s record (`OpticalProperties/Dispersive.fs:90-95`). This part MUST NOT re-derive the matrix-exponential or EVD math seams and MUST NOT add a parallel tensor type; it reuses `OpticalProperties` (`MaterialProperties.fs:165`) end to end. The constant-n+ik model MUST emit `EpsWithoutDisp` (`Dispersion.fs:11`) so a non-dispersive entry incurs no closure overhead.

### D.7 Support anisotropic entries through the existing three-index constructor [Standard]

For uniaxial (n_o, n_e) and biaxial (n_x, n_y, n_z) material definitions, `DispersionModels.fs` MUST build the principal-axis tensor by calling the engine's existing three-argument `Eps.fromComplexRefractionIndex (n1, n2, n3)` (`MaterialProperties.fs:87`), mapping uniaxial as `(n_o, n_e, n_o)`. Each principal index MAY itself be a per-axis `DispersionModel` (D.5) so an anisotropic crystal can disperse differently along each axis, exactly as `Langasite` evaluates ordinary and extraordinary indices separately (`OpticalProperties/Dispersive.fs:52-55`). Crystal-axis orientation MUST NOT be implemented here: rotation reuses `Layer.rotate` (`Media.fs:30`) and is owned by the stack editor (Part B). Full hand-entered Œµ/¬µ/œÅ tensors and gyration reuse `Eps.create`/`Mu.create`/`Rho.create` (`MaterialProperties.fs:62,112,138`) and MUST NOT be re-typed in this part.

### D.8 Define the searchable, categorised materials library aggregate [Core]

This part MUST add a module `MaterialLibrary.fs` in `OpticalConstructor.Domain.fsproj` defining `MaterialEntry` ‚Äî a record holding a display name, a category DU `MaterialCategory = Glass | Metal | Semiconductor | Crystal`, an optional `description : string` (reusing the description convention ¬ßA.7, mirroring the engine's `description` fields e.g. `OpticalSystemWithDisp.description`, `Dispersion.fs:141`), and its `OpticalPropertiesWithDisp` (`Dispersion.fs:53`) produced by D.6/D.7 ‚Äî and a `MaterialLibrary` record holding the entry list plus pure search/filter functions `byCategory` and `byNameContains`. Built-in entries MUST include the already-coded `siliconOpticalProperties` and `langasiteOpticalProperties` (`OpticalProperties/Dispersive.fs:98,99`) and the `Standard` glass/crystal presets (`OpticalProperties/Standard.fs:64-70`) wrapped as `MaterialEntry` values; this part MUST NOT re-derive their dispersion. The library is in-memory and additive; persistence of the library is the JSON `materialEntry` `$def` (¬ßA.7) handled by Part A's storage seam, and a separate shareable library file format is owned by Part I (¬ßI.8). Search indexing/caching is OUT OF SCOPE ‚Äî filtering is a linear `List.filter`.

### D.9 Import from refractiveindex.info YAML and CSV; export CSV [Core]

This part MUST add a module `MaterialImport.fs` in `OpticalConstructor.Storage.fsproj` providing `importRefractiveIndexInfo : string -> Result<MaterialEntry, ImportError>` and `importCsv : string -> Result<MaterialEntry, ImportError>`, parsing the open refractiveindex.info YAML layout (tabulated `n`/`k` vs Œª, and the `formula 1..` Sellmeier/Cauchy coefficient blocks) and tab/comma data via FSharp.Data (the import library named in ¬ßA.7). Every parsed wavelength column MUST be reduced to the engine base by D.2 according to the file's declared unit (refractiveindex.info tabulates Œª in ¬µm), producing either a tabulated `WaveLength -> ComplexRefractionIndex` closure or a `DispersionModel` (D.5) that feeds D.6. Tabulated entries MUST interpolate between sampled points so the resulting closure is total over the chart range; interpolation is linear in Œª and MUST NOT introduce a caching layer. Export MUST provide `exportCsv : MaterialEntry -> Range<WaveLength> -> string` sampling n,k over the range using the entry's `OpticalPropertiesWithDisp.getEps` (`Dispersion.fs:13`). YAML export, retries, and schema-versioned import are OUT OF SCOPE; `Result<_, ImportError>` is the error channel (errors as values, not exceptions). The canonical project still serialises as JSON (¬ßA.7) ‚Äî these importers produce in-memory `MaterialEntry` values and MUST NOT pickle them with FsPickler.

### D.10 Route library entries into the existing dispersion-preview plots with a spectral-unit toggle [Standard]

The material-preview surface in `OpticalConstructor.Ui.fsproj` MUST plot n(Œª)/k(Œª) (and œÅ, Œµ components) by calling the engine's existing `plotN11`/`plotXi11`/`plotN22`/`plotXi22`/`plotN33`/`plotXi33`/`plotRho11` functions (`Analytics/Charting.fs:95-107`), passing the selected `MaterialEntry`'s `OpticalPropertiesWithDisp` (D.8) and a `Range<WaveLength>` (`Variables.fs:22`) built from the user's range. This part MUST NOT re-implement dispersion plotting. The spectral axis MUST expose a unit toggle covering nm / ¬µm / √Ö / eV / cm‚Åª¬π implemented by D.2's `wavelengthToUnit` at the chart boundary ONLY; the underlying `Range<WaveLength>` and the engine data stay in canonical meters (the toggle relabels/rescales the axis, it does not re-store data). Building the `Range<WaveLength>` from user-entered endpoints MUST use D.2 `toWaveLength` so an EUV user can request the range in eV and a green-laser user in nm without manual conversion.

### D.11 Forbid non-SI storage and duplicate-conversion paths [Core]

No module added by this part MAY store a value in a non-SI unit in any domain record, JSON payload, or `.binz` sidecar (¬ß0 constraint 3). The `defaultUnit`/`wavelengthUnit` labels (D.4, D.5) are the ONLY persisted unit names and they label *display intent*, never the datum. All unit arithmetic MUST go through `Units.fs` (D.2); any other module needing a conversion MUST call those functions rather than multiplying by a literal factor. This part MUST NOT add backwards-compatibility shims for pre-existing material files, MUST NOT add a config knob to change the canonical base, and MUST NOT introduce a second wavelength type alongside the engine's `WaveLength` (`Fields.fs:280`).

### D.12 Temperature/composition dependence (thermo-optic dn/dT) as optional model parameters [Standard]

`DispersionModels.fs` MUST support the [Standard] temperature/composition dependence of 010 ¬ß2 (thermo-optic dn/dT, 010 lines 164-165) as OPTIONAL parameters on a `DispersionModel`, never as a mandatory field. This part MUST add a net-new record `ThermoOptic = { dndT : float<1/K>; referenceTemperature : float<K> }` in `DispersionModels.fs` and an OPTIONAL `thermoOptic : ThermoOptic option` carried alongside the model's coefficient record; when `None`, evaluation (D.6) MUST be byte-for-byte the isothermal result with no closure overhead (mirroring the `EpsWithoutDisp` no-overhead rule of D.6). When `Some`, the `evaluate` closure (D.6) MUST apply a first-order thermo-optic correction `n(Œª, T) = n(Œª, referenceTemperature) + dndT ¬∑ (T ‚àí referenceTemperature)` at the chosen operating temperature `T : float<K>`, returning a `ComplexRefractionIndex` (`MaterialProperties.fs:43`); the correction MUST compose with the existing closure shape (`OpticalProperties/Dispersive.fs:87`) and MUST NOT introduce a parallel tensor type. Temperature MUST be stored in kelvin (the engine has no kelvin measure today; `[<Measure>] K` is net-new and lives in `DispersionModels.fs`, not a shadow of `Constants.fs`), and `dndT` MUST be stored in canonical per-kelvin units ‚Äî neither value is a length/energy, so the ¬ß0 canonical-units rule is satisfied by storing SI K and 1/K, and NO non-SI unit is admitted. The operating temperature `T` MUST be supplied by the caller at the evaluation boundary and MUST NOT be persisted into the per-material coefficient record; only `dndT`/`referenceTemperature` persist, as the `materialEntry` dispersion sub-object's optional thermo-optic fields (the `materialEntry` `$def`, ¬ßA.7). This part MUST NOT add full temperature-dependent Sellmeier tables, composition-interpolation tables, or a thermal-expansion model ‚Äî only the first-order dn/dT optional parameter named in 010 ¬ß2.

---

## Part E ‚Äî Light sources & illumination

### E.0 Problem statement

A source is the head of every beam train: it is the `Source` member of the `ConstructorElement` DU and the head `BeamNode` of the `BeamTree` topology, both defined in Part A ¬ßA.4. This part owns the editor that turns operator-entered wavelength, incidence angle, polarization state, and intensity into the engine's canonical incident-light value, plus the [Standard] extensions for polarization presets, a Poincar√©/ellipse picker, spectral source profiles, cone/acceptance averaging, a Gaussian-beam source, coherent/incoherent flags, and multiple simultaneous sources. The Berreman engine already carries the canonical incident-light type: `IncidentLightInfo` is a record of `waveLength`/`refractionIndex`/`incidenceAngle`/`polarization`/`ellipticity` at `Fields.fs:338`, constructed via `IncidentLightInfo.create` (`Fields.fs:375`) and `IncidentLightInfo.createInclined` (`Fields.fs:384`). The whole of this part MUST treat `IncidentLightInfo` as the single canonical source value and MUST NOT fork or shadow it (Part A binding constraint 2).

The [Core] editor is a thin projection: every field of the source editor maps one-to-one onto a field of `IncidentLightInfo`. Wavelength is `WaveLength` (`Mkm | Nm`, `.value : double<meter>`, `Fields.fs:280`); the editor stores it in the canonical meters base via `.value` and converts to/from the operator's chosen display unit ONLY at the UI boundary (Part A binding constraint 3, ¬ßA.10 eV/cm‚Åª¬π conversions). Incidence angle is `IncidenceAngle` (`Fields.fs:22`); polarization is `Polarization` (`Fields.fs:314`); the elliptical state is `Ellipticity` (`Fields.fs:302`, `.create` clamps to [-1, 1] at `Fields.fs:306`). Incident-medium refractive index is `RefractionIndex` (`MaterialProperties.fs:35`, `.vacuum` at `:40`). Single-value-or-range wavelength and angle reuse the existing range primitives in `StandardLightVariables.fs` ‚Äî they are not re-invented here, and the sweep machinery itself belongs to Part F.

The [Standard] features layer on top WITHOUT changing the canonical type. Polarization presets (s, p, 45¬∞, RCP, LCP, unpolarized) are constructions of `Polarization`/`Ellipticity`, reusing `Polarization.s`/`.p`/`.minusP` (`Fields.fs:322-324`). The Poincar√©/ellipse picker is a bidirectional UI gadget over the same two fields plus a derived `StokesVector` (`Fields.fs:580`) for display, reusing `EmField.stokesVector` (`FieldFunctions.fs:44`) for the readout. Spectral profiles, cone/acceptance, and multiple sources are net-new orchestration records that each EXPAND a base `IncidentLightInfo` into a list of `IncidentLightInfo` to feed the solver; incoherent/unpolarized averaging is performed on `StokesVector`/intensity outputs, not on fields. The Gaussian-beam source reuses the engine's FFT scaffolding `createGaussian` (`FourierTransform.fs:74`) and `FourierTransform` (`FourierTransform.fs:137`); it does not introduce a new transform.

This part introduces a top-level operator surface (the Source editor panel) but no long-running background job and no destructive action of its own, so the Operator-facing UX checklist applies only to its single trigger ‚Äî discoverability/nav of the Source panel ‚Äî addressed in E.10. Caching of expanded source lists, retry/error-wrapping shims, schema versioning, config knobs beyond the named per-source default unit, and backwards-compatibility/migration code are OUT OF SCOPE for this part; any such artefact MUST be dropped unless a directive below names it.

### E.1 Source domain record (MUST, net-new, reuses `IncidentLightInfo`)

MUST add a new file `OpticalConstructor.Domain/SourceSpec.fs` to `OpticalConstructor.Domain.fsproj` (Part A assembly layout) defining the net-new orchestration record `SourceSpec` that wraps the canonical `IncidentLightInfo` (`Fields.fs:338`) and carries ONLY the orchestration fields that have no engine equivalent: a stable `sourceId`, an optional `name : string`, the per-source default unit of measure `displayUnit : UnitOfMeasure` (the `unitOfMeasure` `$def` owned by ¬ßA.7, projected to the `sourceSpec` `$def`), an optional `spectralProfile : SpectralProfile option` (E.4), an optional `cone : ConeAcceptance option` (E.5), an optional `gaussianBeam : GaussianBeamSpec option` (E.6), and `coherence : Coherence` (E.7). `SourceSpec` MUST store the base monochromatic state as one `IncidentLightInfo` value and MUST NOT duplicate its five fields. The record MUST be an immutable F# record (Part A constraint 1; CLAUDE.md). It MUST NOT carry any non-SI unit: wavelength lives inside `IncidentLightInfo.waveLength` whose `.value` is meters (`Fields.fs:284`), and `displayUnit` is a presentation-only tag.

### E.2 [Core] Source editor ‚Üí `IncidentLightInfo` projection (MUST)

MUST add `OpticalConstructor.Ui/Sources/SourceEditorView.fs` to `OpticalConstructor.Ui.fsproj` rendering the [Core] editor with one control per `IncidentLightInfo` field: wavelength (single value, with range deferred to E.3), incidence angle, polarization, ellipticity, and intensity. The view MUST be a pure FuncUI view function of the `SourceSpec` model and MUST emit messages that rebuild the underlying `IncidentLightInfo` via a single constructor function `SourceSpec.toIncidentLight : SourceSpec -> IncidentLightInfo`, which MUST be built on `IncidentLightInfo.create` (`Fields.fs:375`) for the normal-incidence case and `IncidentLightInfo.createInclined` (`Fields.fs:384`) for a non-zero angle, then set `polarization`/`ellipticity`/`refractionIndex` via record copy. The view MUST NOT call the 4√ó4 solver; producing fields is owned by Part F. Wavelength entry MUST accept the display unit chosen in `displayUnit` and convert to a `WaveLength` case (`Fields.fs:280`) at the boundary; nm and ¬µm map directly to `WaveLength.Nm`/`WaveLength.Mkm` (`Fields.fs:294,295`), while √Ö, mm, eV, and cm‚Åª¬π MUST be converted to nm or ¬µm via the ¬ßA.10 boundary conversions (Part D `Units.fs` `toWaveLength`, ¬ßD.2) before constructing `WaveLength` (the engine has no `WaveLength` case for those units ‚Äî confirmed: only `Mkm | Nm` at `Fields.fs:280-282`). Intensity MUST be stored as a unit scalar `1.0` baseline on `SourceSpec`; the engine's relative R/T outputs (`FieldFunctions.fs` `intensity`, `:69`) are already normalized to incident, so intensity MUST act only as a per-source weight in multi-source averaging (E.8) and MUST NOT be threaded into `IncidentLightInfo`, which has no intensity field (`Fields.fs:338-345`).

### E.3 [Core] Single-value-or-range wavelength and angle (MUST, reuses range primitives)

MUST express the "wavelength (single or range)" and angle inputs of the [Core] editor as a discriminated union `SourceAxis = Fixed of <value> | Ranged of RangedVariable` inside `SourceSpec.fs`, reusing `RangedVariable` (`Variables.fs:42`) for the ranged case rather than defining a new range type. For wavelength the ranged case MUST use `RangedVariable.WaveLengthRange` (`Variables.fs:46`) and for angle `RangedVariable.IncidenceAngleRange` (`Variables.fs:43`); preset spans MUST reuse the helpers in `StandardLightVariables.fs` (`wavelength200to800Range` `:64`, `incidenceAngleRange` `:40`, `polarizationRange` `:56`, `ellipticityRange` `:48`) instead of constructing fresh `Range<_>` values. The editor MUST surface a Fixed/Ranged toggle; when `Ranged` is chosen the produced `RangedVariable` MUST be handed to the sweep layer (Part F) unchanged. This part MUST NOT implement the sweep execution, charting, or `calculate`/`calculate3D` wiring (`Variables.fs`) ‚Äî only the construction of the `RangedVariable` from operator input.

### E.4 [Standard] Polarization presets + Poincar√©/ellipse picker (MUST)

MUST add `OpticalConstructor.Ui/Sources/PolarizationPicker.fs` exposing the [Standard] presets s, p, 45¬∞, RCP, LCP, and unpolarized as a preset list that sets `IncidentLightInfo.polarization`/`ellipticity` (and the `unpolarized` flag of E.7), reusing `Polarization.s` (`Fields.fs:322`), `Polarization.p` (`Fields.fs:323`), and `Polarization.create (Angle.degree 45.0)` (`Fields.fs:319`); RCP/LCP MUST set `Ellipticity.create 1.0`/`Ellipticity.create -1.0` (`Fields.fs:306`, which clamps to ¬±1). The picker MUST render the polarization ellipse and a Poincar√©-sphere marker as a bidirectional control: dragging azimuth/ellipticity MUST write back `Polarization`/`Ellipticity`, and the live `StokesVector` readout MUST be computed from the produced incident `EmField` via `EmField.stokesVector` (`FieldFunctions.fs:44`) ‚Äî the picker MUST NOT re-derive Stokes parameters by hand. `unpolarized` MUST be represented as the E.7 `Coherence.Unpolarized` flag, not as a sentinel `Polarization`/`Ellipticity` value. The 3D Poincar√© rendering MUST reuse the OpenTK viewport stack named in Part A's `OpticalConstructor.Ui.fsproj` row; this part MUST NOT add a second 3D renderer.

### E.5 [Standard] Spectral source profiles (MUST, net-new)

MUST define a net-new DU `SpectralProfile = Flat | Blackbody of double<K> | Illuminant of StandardIlluminant | LaserLine of WaveLength | ImportedSpectrum of string` in `SourceSpec.fs`, where `StandardIlluminant = D65 | A`, the `LaserLine` payload reuses `WaveLength` (`Fields.fs:280`), and `ImportedSpectrum` carries a sidecar path to a tabulated Œª‚Üíweight spectrum. A `SpectralProfile` MUST be expanded ‚Äî at the UI/IO boundary by a pure function `SpectralProfile.sample : SpectralProfile -> RangedVariable -> (WaveLength * float) list` in `SourceSpec.fs` ‚Äî into a list of (wavelength, spectral weight) pairs over the wavelength range of E.3, each pair producing one `IncidentLightInfo` for the solver and a weight for E.8 averaging. The blackbody, D65, and A weight tables MUST be computed/stored in canonical SI (wavelength in meters via `WaveLength.value`, `Fields.fs:284`); temperature MUST be stored in kelvin. `ImportedSpectrum` MUST reference a sidecar by relative path under the JSON-canonical project (Part A constraint 4) and MUST be parsed with FSharp.Data (Part A storage seam); it MUST NOT be embedded as a `.binz` pickle of the project model. Photometric/CIE conversion of the resulting spectra is owned by the analysis part (Part F ¬ßF.8), not here.

### E.6 [Standard] Cone / acceptance averaging (MUST, net-new)

MUST define a net-new record `ConeAcceptance = { halfAngle : Angle; samples : int }` in `SourceSpec.fs` (`Angle` is the engine geometry type already wrapped by `IncidenceAngle`, `Fields.fs:22`). A `ConeAcceptance` MUST be expanded by a pure function `ConeAcceptance.sample : ConeAcceptance -> IncidenceAngle -> IncidenceAngle list` that fans the base incidence angle into `samples` sub-angles across ¬±`halfAngle`, each producing one `IncidentLightInfo` via record copy on `incidenceAngle`. The expanded angles MUST be averaged on the OUTPUT side ‚Äî over the solver's `StokesVector`/intensity results (`FieldFunctions.fs:44,69`) ‚Äî and MUST NOT be averaged on the field amplitudes. Collimated illumination MUST be represented by the absence of a `ConeAcceptance` (`cone = None`), not by a zero-angle cone. Detector-acceptance averaging that belongs to a detector element is out of scope for this part; only the source-side cone is defined here.

### E.7 [Standard] Coherent / incoherent and unpolarized flags (MUST, net-new)

MUST define a net-new DU `Coherence = Coherent | Incoherent | Unpolarized` in `SourceSpec.fs` carried on `SourceSpec.coherence`. `Coherent` is the default and MUST map directly to the engine's existing coherent solve (`OpticalSystemSolver`, `Solvers.fs:199`) with no change. `Incoherent` MUST be honored by routing the source through the engine's existing thick-substrate multi-reflection path ‚Äî the substrate-driven `Multiple` solution branch (`Solvers.fs:152`, `Solution.create` at `:176`) that already sums intensities incoherently over internal reflections via `MultipleEmFieldSystem` (`Fields.fs:571`); this part MUST NOT add a separate incoherent solver. The per-layer coherent/incoherent split (thick substrate incoherent while films stay coherent) is a property of the stack/substrate (`Substrate = Plate | Wedge`, Part A ¬ßA.4 / `Media.fs:40`) owned by Part B ‚Äî this directive owns ONLY the source-level flag that selects the path. `Unpolarized` MUST be expanded into the incoherent average of two orthogonal polarizations built from `Polarization.s`/`Polarization.p` (`Fields.fs:322,323`), averaged on `StokesVector`/intensity output (E.8), and MUST NOT be modeled by mutating `Ellipticity`.

### E.8 [Standard] Multiple sources and averaging (MUST, net-new, reuses `MultipleEmFieldSystem`)

MUST allow a project to hold a list `sources : SourceSpec list` on the `OpticalConstructorProject` aggregate (the `sources` field declared in Part A ¬ßA.7); this part owns the `sourceSpec` `$def` shape and the list semantics. Each `SourceSpec` MUST expand ‚Äî via a single pure function `SourceSpec.expand : SourceSpec -> (IncidentLightInfo * float) list` composing E.4/E.5/E.6/E.7 ‚Äî into a list of weighted `IncidentLightInfo` values. The combined illumination MUST be evaluated by solving each expanded `IncidentLightInfo` with the existing single-system solver and combining the resulting `StokesVector`/intensity outputs as a weighted incoherent sum, reusing `StokesVector.(+)` and `StokesVector.Zero` (`Fields.fs:584,586`) for the accumulation; field-level (`EmField`) values MUST NOT be summed across sources. The weighted-sum reducer MUST live in `OpticalConstructor.Domain/SourceCombination.fs`. This part MUST NOT add caching of expanded source lists, retry logic, or a parallel scheduler; expansion is recomputed from the immutable `SourceSpec` on demand (Part A constraint 6).

### E.9 [Standard] Gaussian-beam source (MUST, reuses FFT scaffolding)

MUST define a net-new record `GaussianBeamSpec = { waist : double<meter>; divergence : Angle }` in `SourceSpec.fs`, storing the beam waist in canonical meters (Part A constraint 3). The angular spectrum of the Gaussian beam MUST be generated by reusing the engine's existing scaffolding ‚Äî `createGaussian` (`FourierTransform.fs:74`) for the Gaussian profile and the `FourierTransform` module (`FourierTransform.fs:137`) for the transform ‚Äî inside a pure function `GaussianBeamSpec.angularSpectrum : GaussianBeamSpec -> WaveLength -> (IncidenceAngle * float) list` in `SourceSpec.fs`. This function MUST NOT introduce a new FFT, a new Gaussian generator, or a separate beam-propagation engine; it MUST produce a weighted set of plane-wave incidence angles that feed the same `expand`/averaging path as E.6/E.8. Beam propagation between curved elements (focusing) is owned by the curved-optics part (Part C), not here; this directive owns ONLY the source-side decomposition of the beam into weighted plane waves.

### E.10 Operator UX ‚Äî Source panel discoverability (MUST)

MUST register the Source editor (E.2) as a named entry in the constructor's element-palette/navigation so the operator can add a `Source` element (the `ConstructorElement.Source` case, Part A ¬ßA.4) and open its editor; the panel MUST be reachable from the palette without a hidden command. Because this part introduces no long-running background job and no destructive action, the remaining Operator-facing UX checklist items (progress granularity, pre-confirmation gate, completion‚Üíresults refresh, opposing-action/undo, committable-file vs .gitignore) are NOT triggered here and MUST NOT be implemented in this part; sweep progress and results refresh are owned by Part F, and project-file persistence/undo by Part I. Adding a source MUST be a one-click palette action with no confirmation gate (a source is non-destructive and freely removable from the `sources` list of E.8).

