## Part F ‚Äî Calculations & analysis

### F.0 Problem statement

The Berreman engine already computes the physics that Part II ¬ß4 of 010 asks the Optical Constructor to surface: reflectance/transmittance with the s/p split, Stokes vectors, Jones and Mueller matrices, ellipticity, azimuth, and the in-layer E/H/D/B/Poynting fields. The 4√ó4 single-system solver (`Solvers.fs:199` `OpticalSystemSolver`), the field outputs on `EmField`/`EmFieldSystem`/`Solution` (`FieldFunctions.fs:44,74,82,142,190`), and the 1D/3D sweep+chart pipeline (`Variables.fs:237` `calculate`, `Variables.fs:270` `calculate3D`, `Charting.fs:21` `plot`) are the primitives this part stands on. This part is therefore predominantly an analysis/derivation layer that reads solver outputs and presents the ¬ß4 quantities; it MUST NOT fork or re-derive the solver, the field model, or the math seam (Part A constraint 2).

The work that is genuinely net-new is narrow and named in 010: (a) the per-`EmField` `muellerMatrix` member is commented out at `FieldFunctions.fs:93` and MUST be completed; (b) ellipsometric Œ®, Œî and the (N, C, S) triple are not present in the tree and MUST be derived from the existing s/p field amplitudes; (c) an explicit per-layer absorptance / total-absorbed-power breakdown is not present and MUST be derived from the Poynting flux the engine already computes; (d) a CIE XYZ/Lab/sRGB color conversion from an R or T spectrum is net-new; and (e) the in-layer field/EFI depth profile MUST be assembled by sampling the existing `EmField.propagate` seam (`BerremanMatrix.fs:224`). The Mueller-matrix *system-level* path is, contrary to a literal reading of 010, already implemented at `Solvers.fs:286,315,316` (`getMuellerMatrix`, `muellerMatrixR()`, `muellerMatrixT()`) and at the `StokesVector`‚Üí`MuellerMatrix` constructors (`Fields.fs:601,636,643`); this part MUST reuse those and MUST NOT shadow them.

All derived quantities in this part are pure functions of a `Solution` (`Solvers.fs:152`) or of the field amplitudes inside it. They are computed in canonical SI internally (wavelength via `WaveLength.value`, `Fields.fs:284`); any nm/eV/cm‚Åª¬π axis labelling is the UI/IO boundary's job (Part A ¬ßA.10) and is OUT OF SCOPE here. The convergence control this part exposes is the single existing knob `SolverParameters.numberOfReflections` (`Solvers.fs:15`); no new numerical thresholds are invented, and no `almostZero`/`almostZeroDet` constant (`Constants.fs:41,45`) is re-tuned.

Scope boundary for this part: caching of sweep results beyond the `.binz` sidecar already mandated by Part A ¬ßA.7, retry/resume of long sweeps, alternate optimization-driven analyses (those belong to Part G), schema-versioning of the new result records, and any new math-seam backend are OUT OF SCOPE. New analysis modules are admitted ONLY where a directive below names them and traces them to a ¬ß4 feature with no engine equivalent.

### F.1 ‚Äî [Core] Spectral & angular R/T/A scans (s/p split) MUST reuse the existing `OpticalFunction` outputs and the `calculate` sweep

The spectral/angular scan of R, T, and the s/p split MUST be produced by `Variables.calculate` (`Variables.fs:237`) driven by a `WaveLengthRange` or `IncidenceAngleRange` `RangedVariable` (`Variables.fs:42,43,46`), reading the per-point `Solution.func` outputs `R`, `Rp`, `Rs`, `T`, `Tp`, `Ts` (`FieldFunctions.fs:130-135,192`). The absorption channel A = 1 ‚àí R ‚àí T MUST be a new pure function `absorptance (s : Solution) : float` placed in a new module file `Analytics/AnalysisFunctions.fs`, computed as `(s.func R, s.func T) |> fun (r, t) -> 1.0 - (defaultArg r 0.0) - (defaultArg t 0.0)`; it MUST reuse `Solution.func` and MUST NOT call the solver again. The s/p split is already carried by the distinct `Rp`/`Rs`/`Tp`/`Ts` cases ‚Äî no new split logic is admitted. This directive adds NO new sweep engine: 1D scans go through `calculate`/`plot` (`Variables.fs:237`, `Charting.fs:21`) and the 2D R-vs-Œª√óangle surface goes through `calculate3D`/`plot3D` (`Variables.fs:270`, `Charting.fs:64`).

### F.2 ‚Äî [Core] Parameter sweeps MUST be expressed as `RangedVariable` cases, not a new sweep abstraction

Sweeps over thickness, angle, polarization, ellipticity, wedge angle, or an arbitrary model parameter MUST be expressed by constructing the existing `RangedVariable` (`Variables.fs:42`): `IncidenceAngleRange`, `PolarizationRange`, `EllipticityRange`, `WaveLengthRange`, `WedgeAngleRange`, and ‚Äî for thickness or any material parameter ‚Äî `ArbitraryVariableRange` carrying an `ArbitraryVariable` (`Variables.fs:32`) whose `getSys : OpticalSystem -> double -> OpticalSystem` mutates the system at each sweep point. The UI/orchestration layer MUST build these values; this part MUST NOT introduce a parallel sweep descriptor type. Bulk sweep output (the `array<float * Solution>` from `calculate`, or the 2D array from `calculate3D`) MUST be persisted ONLY as a `.binz` sidecar via `Softellect.Sys.Core.serialize` with `BinaryZippedFormat` (`C:/GitHub/Softellect/Sys/Core.fs:257`) per Part A ¬ßA.7 ‚Äî never inside the canonical JSON project. No retry, resume, or incremental-cache layer is added.

### F.3 ‚Äî [Standard] Complete the commented-out per-`EmField` Mueller path and add the Stokes/Jones/Mueller accessors

The commented-out member `member em.muellerMatrix : MuellerMatrix` at `FieldFunctions.fs:93` MUST be implemented by delegating to the existing constructor `MuellerMatrix.fromEmFields` (`Fields.fs:636`), supplying the field's own s- and p-resolved components ‚Äî it MUST NOT re-derive the 4√ó4 Mueller algebra, which already exists at `MuellerMatrix.create` (`Fields.fs:601`). The system-level Mueller matrices MUST be obtained from the already-implemented `OpticalSystemSolver.muellerMatrixR()` / `muellerMatrixT()` (`Solvers.fs:315,316`); this part MUST NOT add a second system-level Mueller routine. The Stokes vector per field is read from `EmField.stokesVector` (`FieldFunctions.fs:44`); the per-`Solution` incident/reflected/transmitted Stokes vectors are read from `Solution.stokesI`/`stokesR`/`stokesT` (`FieldFunctions.fs:222,227,238`). A new pure function `stokesSystem (s : Solution) : StokesSystem` in `Analytics/AnalysisFunctions.fs` MUST assemble the existing-but-unconstructed `StokesSystem` record (`Fields.fs:590`) from those three accessors. The Jones matrices MUST be read from `JonesMatrix.fromEmFields` (`Fields.fs:679`); no Jones algebra is re-implemented.

### F.4 ‚Äî [Standard] Degree of polarization MUST be derived from the existing Stokes vector

The degree of polarization MUST be a new pure function `degreeOfPolarization (StokesVector v) : float` in `Analytics/AnalysisFunctions.fs`, computed as `sqrt(s1¬≤ + s2¬≤ + s3¬≤) / s0` from the four components of the `StokesVector` (`Fields.fs:580`), reusing `Solution.stokesR`/`stokesT` (`FieldFunctions.fs:227,238`) as its inputs. Ellipticity and azimuth are NOT re-derived here ‚Äî they are already exposed as `EmFieldSystem.ellipticityR`/`ellipticityT`/`azimuthR`/`azimuthT` (`FieldFunctions.fs:157,161,165,169`) and as the `EllipticityR`/`EllipticityT`/`AzimuthR`/`AzimuthT` `OpticalFunction` cases (`FieldFunctions.fs:119-122,184-187`); this part MUST surface those existing functions, not new ones.

### F.5 ‚Äî [Standard] Ellipsometric Œ®, Œî and (N, C, S) MUST be derived from the reflected s/p amplitudes

A new module-level set of pure functions `psiDelta (s : Solution) : float * float` and `ncs (s : Solution) : float * float * float` MUST be added to `Analytics/AnalysisFunctions.fs`. They MUST form the complex ellipsometric ratio œÅ = r_pp / r_ss from the reflected field's s- and p-resolved amplitudes `EmField.amplitudeS` / `EmField.amplitudeP` (`Fields.fs:520,530`) taken from the reflected solutions of `OpticalSystemSolver.solutionS()` / `solutionP()` (`Solvers.fs:313,314`) ‚Äî reusing the exact s/p decomposition that `getMuellerMatrix` already relies on (`Solvers.fs:286`). Œ® and Œî MUST be `tan Œ® = |œÅ|`, `Œî = arg œÅ`; the (N, C, S) triple MUST be `N = cos 2Œ®`, `C = sin 2Œ® cos Œî`, `S = sin 2Œ® sin Œî`. These functions MUST NOT call into the optimizer and MUST NOT introduce a new field-amplitude extraction path; `amplitudeS`/`amplitudeP` are the single source. Part G ¬ßG.6 reuses this same s/p ellipsometric derivation for fit residuals and MUST NOT fork it. Œ®/Œî-vs-Œª and Œ®/Œî-vs-angle plots reuse `calculate`/`plot` by mapping these functions over the per-point `Solution`, mirroring how `Charting.plot` maps `Solution.func` (`Charting.fs:26-31`).

### F.6 ‚Äî [Standard] In-layer field / EFI depth profile MUST be sampled via the existing `EmField.propagate` seam

The |E|¬≤/Poynting-vs-depth profile MUST be produced by a new pure function `fieldDepthProfile (system : OpticalSystem) (info : IncidentLightInfo) (samplesPerLayer : int) : (double<meter> * float) list` in a new file `Analytics/FieldProfile.fs`. It MUST walk the transmitted `EmField` of the base solution into each `Layer` (`Media.fs:24`) by repeatedly applying the inter-element propagation seam `EmField.propagate (s : Layer)` (`BerremanMatrix.fs:224`) at sub-layer thickness steps cut from the layer's `Thickness` (`Media.fs:12`), and at each depth read `EmField.e` for |E|¬≤ and `EmField.s` (the Poynting vector, `Fields.fs:434`) for power flow. It MUST reuse `BaseOpticalSystemSolver` (`Solvers.fs:115`) to obtain the entry field and MUST NOT re-solve the 4√ó4 system per depth sample. The known limitation noted in the engine (`BerremanMatrix.fs:221`, "Does not work properly yet") is carried forward as-is ‚Äî this part wires the profile through that seam and MUST NOT attempt to rewrite `propagate`. The depth axis is stored in meters; nm/¬µm display is the UI boundary's concern (Part A ¬ßA.10).

### F.7 ‚Äî [Standard] Per-layer absorptance and total absorbed power MUST be derived from the Poynting flux at layer boundaries

A new pure function `layerAbsorptance (system : OpticalSystem) (info : IncidentLightInfo) : (Layer * float) list` and a `totalAbsorbedPower` aggregate MUST be added to `Analytics/FieldProfile.fs`. Each layer's absorptance MUST be the drop in normal Poynting flux across that layer, computed from `EmField.s` (`Fields.fs:434`) of the propagated field at the layer's upper and lower boundaries using the same `EmField.propagate (Layer)` walk as F.6 (`BerremanMatrix.fs:224`); the per-field intensity normalisation MUST reuse `EmField.intensity` (`FieldFunctions.fs:69`) against the incident field. The total absorbed power MUST equal the system-level A from F.1 within solver tolerance, and the function MUST NOT introduce a second absorption definition divergent from `absorptance` (F.1). No new energy-balance constant is introduced.

### F.8 ‚Äî [Standard] Color (CIE XYZ / Lab / sRGB) MUST convert an R or T spectrum sampled over the `WaveLengthRange`

A new file `Analytics/Colorimetry.fs` MUST provide pure functions `spectrumToXyz`, `xyzToLab`, and `xyzToSrgb`. `spectrumToXyz` MUST take the `(float * Solution) array` produced by `Variables.calculate` over a `WaveLengthRange` (`Variables.fs:46,237`) plus a chosen channel (`R` or `T` via the `OpticalFunction` cases, `FieldFunctions.fs:130,133`), integrate the channel against the CIE 1931 2¬∞ colour-matching functions and a chosen illuminant, and return CIE XYZ; `xyzToLab` and `xyzToSrgb` MUST apply the standard CIE Lab and sRGB transforms. The CIE colour-matching tables and the D65/A illuminant tables are embedded constants in this file (the only net-new numeric data this part introduces, traced to 010 ¬ß4 "Color calculation"). These functions MUST consume the sweep output of F.1 and MUST NOT re-run the solver. No alternate colour space beyond XYZ/Lab/sRGB is added.

### F.9 ‚Äî [Standard] Convergence control MUST expose ONLY the existing `SolverParameters.numberOfReflections`

The convergence control surfaced to analysis MUST be the existing field `SolverParameters.numberOfReflections` (`Solvers.fs:15`), threaded into `OpticalSystemSolver(info, system, parameters)` (`Solvers.fs:199`) at the point where this part constructs a solution for a thick `Plate`/`Wedge` substrate (`Media.fs:40`). This part MUST NOT invent new numerical thresholds, MUST NOT re-tune `almostZero` or `almostZeroDet` (`Constants.fs:41,45`), and MUST NOT add a convergence-iteration cache. The default MUST remain `SolverParameters.defaultValue` (`Solvers.fs:21`, `numberOfReflections = 3`) when the caller supplies none, matching what `calculate` already passes (`Variables.fs:266`).

### F.10 ‚Äî All new analysis functions MUST live in the Analytics project and be reachable from the orchestration layer

The new files `Analytics/AnalysisFunctions.fs` (F.1, F.3, F.4, F.5), `Analytics/FieldProfile.fs` (F.6, F.7), and `Analytics/Colorimetry.fs` (F.8) MUST be added to `Analytics/Analytics.fsproj` (`C:/GitHub/Berreman/Berreman/Analytics/Analytics.fsproj:39` shows the `<Compile Include="...">` ordering convention) in dependency order after `FieldFunctions`/`Variables`. They MUST be plain F# modules of pure functions over `Solution`/`EmField`/`OpticalSystem` with no UI, no FuncUI reference (the clone audit gate of Part A ¬ßA.9 is unaffected and remains undecided), and no hidden global state. The `OpticalConstructor.Ui` project (Part A assembly layout) consumes them by import; this part MUST NOT add a UI page itself. The completion of `em.muellerMatrix` (F.3) is an edit to the existing `FieldFunctions.fs:93`, not a new file.

---

## Part G ‚Äî Design synthesis, optimization & fitting

### G.0 Problem statement

The Berreman engine computes the *forward* problem only: given a fully specified `OpticalSystem` (`Media.fs:94`) and an `IncidentLightInfo` (`Fields.fs:338`), `OpticalSystemSolver` (`Solvers.fs:199`) produces the reflected and transmitted fields, from which `FieldFunctions.fs` derives R, T, ellipticity, and azimuth (`FieldFunctions.fs:130,133,157,165`). There is no code in the Berreman tree that runs this forward model *inside* a loop to drive a parameter set toward a target spectrum, and there is no nonlinear-least-squares solver: the only optimization code present is the Math.NET clone's trust-region machinery under `MathNetNumerics/Numerics/Optimization/`, which Part A's math seam does not expose and which ¬ßA.8 of this spec explicitly does not select for fitting. The partial Wolfram/Mathematica `FindMinimum`/`NonlinearModelFit` workflow that this part ports lives outside the repository entirely. This part is therefore almost wholly net-new orchestration above the existing solver.

This part owns the inverse and synthesis half of the application: a target/merit-function editor; local refinement of layer thicknesses (and optionally indices/geometry) by Levenberg‚ÄìMarquardt, quasi-Newton, and Nelder‚ÄìMead simplex with bounded parameters and one-sided/inequality targets; inverse fitting against measured photometric (R/T) and ellipsometric (Œ®, Œî) spectra; fit-quality reporting (œá¬≤/MSE, confidence intervals, correlation matrix, residuals); needle/tunnelling synthesis that grows the layer count; and global optimization (simulated annealing, genetic/evolutionary). Per Part A ¬ßA.8 and the Part A assembly map, **ALGLIB is used for optimization ONLY**, sits behind a library-agnostic optimization interface defined in our own terms, and ITS `minlm` MUST be validated against the Wolfram reference fits. ALGLIB MUST NOT touch linear algebra ‚Äî that stays on the Part A math seam (`MathNetNumericsMath.fs:5`).

The design variables a fit may adjust are layer thicknesses (`Thickness of double<meter>`, `Media.fs:12`), dispersion-model coefficients (`OpticalPropertiesWithDisp`, `Dispersion.fs:53`), and wedge/geometry parameters. The bridge from a flat `float[]` parameter vector (ALGLIB's currency) to a concrete `OpticalSystem` MUST reuse the existing parametrization seam `ArbitraryVariable.getSys : OpticalSystem -> double -> OpticalSystem` (`Variables.fs:37`), which `calculate` already invokes at `Variables.fs:263` to re-derive a system from a scalar ‚Äî the multi-parameter generalization is a list of such mappings, not a new mechanism. The merit residual MUST be assembled from the same `OpticalFunction` evaluators (`FieldFunctions.fs:109`, `Solution.func` `FieldFunctions.fs:192`) that the charting path uses, so that "what the chart shows" and "what the fit minimizes" are computed by one code path.

Œ® and Œî are derived from the reflected/transmitted s/p field amplitudes by Part F ¬ßF.5; 010 ¬ßII.4 tiers them [Standard] as "derivable from existing field amplitudes". This part reuses that same derivation at the optimization boundary for ellipsometric fitting, reusing the complex reflected/transmitted `EmComponent` amplitudes already solved in `getRT` (`Solvers.fs:74`); it MUST NOT fork the solver and MUST NOT re-derive Œ®/Œî independently of ¬ßF.5. All canonical-units, JSON-canonical, `.binz`-derived, and tier-fidelity rules from ¬ß0 apply unchanged: parameter bounds and targets are stored in meters/SI in the JSON project, fit histories are `.binz` sidecars, and human units appear only at the UI boundary.

This part introduces a top-level operator page (the Synthesis/Fit workspace), long-running cancellable background jobs (every optimizer run), and no destructive disk action beyond writing derived sidecars; the operator-facing UX checklist is therefore in scope and addressed in G.10. Caching of forward evaluations beyond a single optimizer run, retry/backoff of failed solves, optimizer-plugin discovery via reflection, config-knob proliferation, schema versioning of the fit payloads, and error-wrapping shims are OUT OF SCOPE and MUST NOT be added; only the artefacts named by the directives below are admitted.

### G.1 Library-agnostic optimization interface

This part MUST define the optimization abstraction in our own terms in a new file `OpticalConstructor.Optimization/OptimizationInterface.fs` inside the `OpticalConstructor.Optimization.fsproj` project named in the Part A assembly map. The interface MUST be expressed as F# records and discriminated unions (¬ß0 constraint 1) and MUST NOT reference any ALGLIB type in its public surface, so the physics/fitting code compiles without the library, per ¬ßA.8 ("the physics/fitting code never depends on ALGLIB directly").

The interface MUST consist of exactly:
- `Residual = float[] -> float[]` ‚Äî the vectorized residual function (one entry per target sample), matching ¬ßA.8's `(float[] -> float[])`.
- `Jacobian = (float[] -> float[][]) option` ‚Äî optional analytic Jacobian; when `None` the adapter MUST request numerical differentiation.
- `ParameterBounds` (record: `lower : float[]`, `upper : float[]`) ‚Äî per-parameter box bounds in canonical SI units (¬ß0 constraint 3); an unbounded side MUST be encoded as `infinity`/`-infinity`.
- `InequalityTarget` (DU: `LessOrEqual | GreaterOrEqual` carrying the bound) ‚Äî the one-sided target from 010 ¬ßII.5 ("R ‚â§ 0.5%").
- `OptimizationMethod` (DU: `LevenbergMarquardt | QuasiNewtonLbfgs | NelderMead | BoundedLinearConstrained | NonlinearConstrained`) ‚Äî the method selector mapping onto the ALGLIB routines named in ¬ßA.8/010 ¬ßIII.4: `LevenbergMarquardt ‚Üí minlm`, `QuasiNewtonLbfgs ‚Üí minlbfgs`, `BoundedLinearConstrained ‚Üí minbleic`, `NonlinearConstrained ‚Üí minnlc`. `NelderMead` is the 010-required simplex method (010 line 219) whose concrete backend 010 leaves unnamed; its routine binding is deferred per G.2 and MUST NOT be resolved to a spec-invented routine here.
- `OptimizationRequest` (record: residual, optional jacobian, initial `float[]`, bounds, inequality targets, method, `maxIterations : int`, `epsX : float`) ‚Äî the single call payload.
- `OptimizationResult` (record: `solution : float[]`, `finalResiduals : float[]`, `iterations : int`, `terminationReason : TerminationReason`, `success : bool`) where `TerminationReason` is a DU (`Converged | MaxIterationsReached | StepTooSmall | Failed of string`).

The interface MUST expose a single entry point `optimize : OptimizationRequest -> Result<OptimizationResult, string>` (¬ß0 error-handling rule: `Result`, not exceptions). No caching, retry, or progress-callback registry is admitted in this file; progress reporting is wired in G.10 via a separate channel.

### G.2 ALGLIB adapter behind the interface

This part MUST implement the interface from G.1 in a new file `OpticalConstructor.Optimization/AlglibAdapter.fs`, the ONLY file in the solution permitted to `open`/reference ALGLIB. ALGLIB MUST be added as a NuGet `PackageReference` to `OpticalConstructor.Optimization.fsproj` (no new C# project ‚Äî ¬ß0 constraint 1); the GPL free edition is the licensed edition per ¬ßA.8.

The adapter MUST map each `OptimizationMethod` to the ALGLIB routine named in ¬ßA.8: `LevenbergMarquardt ‚Üí minlm` (`minlmcreatev`/`minlmcreatevj` when a Jacobian is supplied, with `minlmsetbc` for bounds), `QuasiNewtonLbfgs ‚Üí minlbfgs`, `BoundedLinearConstrained ‚Üí minbleic`, `NonlinearConstrained ‚Üí minnlc`. `NelderMead` is the [Standard] Nelder‚ÄìMead simplex method 010 ¬ßII.5 requires (010 line 219), but 010 ¬ßIII.4 names NO ALGLIB routine for a simplex solver ‚Äî its list is exactly `minlm`/`minbleic`/`minnlc`/`minlbfgs`/`mincg`/`lsfit` (010 lines 380-382). This part MUST NOT invent an ALGLIB routine name for the simplex case; the following deferred decision is carried forward VERBATIM as a directive: **the concrete simplex backend for `NelderMead` ‚Äî an ALGLIB routine if one is later confirmed to exist, OR an explicit in-file F# Nelder‚ÄìMead loop over the G.1 `Residual` closure ‚Äî is deliberately undecided here and MUST remain undecided until that decision is taken, traceable to the 010-required simplex feature; this part MUST NOT resolve it by binding `NelderMead` to a spec-invented ALGLIB routine.** Until that decision is taken the adapter MUST surface `NelderMead` as `Failed "simplex backend unresolved"` rather than silently dispatching to a guessed routine. The adapter MUST translate `ParameterBounds` into the routine's box-constraint call and `InequalityTarget`s into either residual penalty rows (for `minlm`) or nonlinear constraints (for `minnlc`); it MUST convert ALGLIB's completion codes into `TerminationReason` and MUST NOT leak an ALGLIB exception past the `Result` boundary. Linear algebra inside the adapter (normal-equation/QR solves for the LM step) is ALGLIB's own; this part MUST NOT route any matrix operation through `MathNetNumericsMath.fs:5`, and conversely MUST NOT use ALGLIB for any engine linear algebra (¬ßA.8: "ALGLIB is used for optimization only, not for linear algebra"). Extreme Optimization MUST NOT be referenced from this adapter; `ExtremeNumericsMath.fs:5` remains a legacy math-seam reference only, per ¬ßA.8.

### G.3 Parameter ‚áÑ system mapping (design variables)

This part MUST define the bridge from a flat `float[]` parameter vector to a concrete `OpticalSystem` in a new file `OpticalConstructor.Optimization/DesignParameters.fs`, reusing the existing scalar parametrization seam `ArbitraryVariable.getSys : OpticalSystem -> double -> OpticalSystem` (`Variables.fs:37`) that `calculate` already calls at `Variables.fs:263`. A `DesignParameter` (new record) MUST carry a `name : string`, a `getSys : OpticalSystem -> double -> OpticalSystem` closure (the same signature as `ArbitraryVariable.getSys`), and the per-parameter SI bound pair; an ordered `DesignParameter list` MUST fold left over a base `OpticalSystem` to apply the whole `float[]` vector, in vector order.

The supported design variables MUST be: **layer thickness** ‚Äî the closure MUST rebuild the target `Layer` with `Thickness (v * 1.0<meter>)` (`Media.fs:12`), v already in canonical meters (¬ß0 constraint 3); **dispersion coefficient** ‚Äî the closure MUST substitute into the relevant `OpticalPropertiesWithDisp` (`Dispersion.fs:53`) field; **wedge angle** ‚Äî the closure MUST set the `WedgeLayer.angle` (`Media.fs:34`). Negative-thickness prohibition and physical n-range bounding (010 ¬ßII.5) MUST be expressed as the `ParameterBounds` of G.1 (lower bound 0 for thickness), NOT as a separate validator. This file MUST NOT introduce reflection-based field setting; every mapping is an explicit F# closure the reader can follow (¬ß0 locality rule).

### G.4 Target / merit-function editor [Core]

This part MUST define the merit/target model in a new file `OpticalConstructor.Optimization/MeritFunction.fs` and surface it in the UI per G.10, carrying the **[Core]** tier from 010 ¬ßII.5. A `FitTarget` (new record) MUST carry: the `OpticalFunction` to evaluate (reuse `FieldFunctions.fs:109`: `R | Rp | Rs | T | Tp | Ts | EllipticityR | ‚Ä¶`, extended for Œ®/Œî per G.6), the independent-variable sample point (a `RangedVariable` index or explicit `WaveLength`/`IncidenceAngle`, reusing `Variables.fs:42`), the desired value, a `weight : float`, a `tolerance : float`, and a `kind : TargetKind` DU (`Equality | Inequality of InequalityTarget`) ‚Äî covering 010 ¬ßII.5's "weights, tolerances, and one-sided/inequality targets".

The merit function MUST be assembled as a weighted least-squares residual vector: for each `FitTarget`, residual = weight √ó (modelValue ‚àí desiredValue) / max(tolerance, Œµ) for `Equality`, and a one-sided hinge (zero when satisfied) for `Inequality`. `modelValue` MUST be obtained by running `OpticalSystemSolver` (`Solvers.fs:199`) on the system produced by the G.3 mapping at the target's sample point and reading `Solution.func` (`FieldFunctions.fs:192`) ‚Äî the SAME evaluator the charts use, so fit and chart never diverge. The assembled residual closure MUST satisfy the `Residual` signature of G.1 directly. Stored `desiredValue`/sample points MUST be canonical SI (meters for wavelength via `WaveLength.value`, `Fields.fs:284`); unit conversion happens only at the editor boundary (¬ß0 constraint 3). No merit-evaluation cache is admitted here.

### G.5 Local refinement optimization [Core]

This part MUST implement local refinement in a new file `OpticalConstructor.Optimization/LocalRefinement.fs`, carrying the **[Core]** tier from 010 ¬ßII.5. The entry point MUST take a base `OpticalSystem`, a `DesignParameter list` (G.3), a `FitTarget list` (G.4), and an `OptimizationMethod` (G.1), build the residual closure, and call `optimize` (G.1). Levenberg‚ÄìMarquardt (`LevenbergMarquardt`) MUST be the default method ("the workhorse", 010 ¬ßII.5); quasi-Newton (`QuasiNewtonLbfgs`) and Nelder‚ÄìMead simplex (`NelderMead`) MUST be selectable. Bounded parameters MUST be honoured by passing the G.3 bounds as `ParameterBounds`, and inequality targets MUST flow through as G.1 `InequalityTarget`s ‚Äî satisfying 010 ¬ßII.5's "bounded parameters and inequality targets (forbid negative thickness, bound n to physical ranges)".

On success the optimizer's `solution` vector MUST be folded back through the G.3 mapping to produce the refined `OpticalSystem`, which becomes the new working system. Robust normal-equation handling (QR / Gauss‚ÄìJordan, 010 ¬ßII.5) is delegated to ALGLIB's `minlm` internals via G.2 and MUST NOT be re-implemented on the math seam. This file MUST NOT spawn its own thread; long-running execution and cancellation are owned by G.10.

### G.6 Œ®, Œî derivation for ellipsometric residuals [Standard]

This part MUST add the ellipsometric quantities Œ® and Œî as evaluable optimization targets in a new file `OpticalConstructor.Optimization/Ellipsometry.fs`, carrying the **[Standard]** tier from 010 ¬ßII.4 ("Œ®, Œî ‚Ä¶ derivable from existing field amplitudes"). The derivation MUST reuse the complex reflected `EmComponent` amplitudes already solved by `getRT` (`Solvers.fs:74`) and exposed on `EmFieldSystem.reflected` (`Fields.fs:550`): the complex ratio œÅ = r_p / r_s yields tan(Œ®)¬∑e^{iŒî}, so Œ® = atan(|œÅ|) and Œî = arg(œÅ). This file MUST NOT fork `Solvers.fs` or `FieldFunctions.fs` (¬ß0 constraint 2); it consumes their outputs and MUST share the Œ®/Œî definition of Part F ¬ßF.5 (`psiDelta`) rather than re-deriving an independent one.

The two new functions MUST be surfaced as additional cases reachable by `FitTarget` (G.4) so ellipsometric targets compose identically to photometric ones. Because `FieldFunctions.fs:109` `OpticalFunction` is closed and ¬ß0 constraint 2 forbids forking it, this part MUST add `Psi` and `Delta` as a small net-new `EllipsometricFunction` DU local to `Ellipsometry.fs` with its own evaluator over `EmFieldSystem`, NOT by editing the engine's `OpticalFunction`. The completion of the Mueller path (`FieldFunctions.fs:93`) is owned by Part F ¬ßF.3 and MUST NOT be revived by this part ‚Äî it is outside the fitting scope named in 010 ¬ßII.5.

### G.7 Inverse fitting from measured R/T and Œ®,Œî [Standard]

This part MUST implement inverse fitting from measured data in a new file `OpticalConstructor.Optimization/InverseFit.fs`, carrying the **[Standard]** tier from 010 ¬ßII.5. Measured photometric (R/T) and ellipsometric (Œ®, Œî) spectra MUST be loaded via FSharp.Data (the import library named in the Part A storage seam and 010 ¬ßIII.2) from CSV/tab sources and converted to canonical SI sample points (wavelength in meters via `WaveLength.value`, `Fields.fs:284`) at the import boundary only.

Each measured spectral point MUST be turned into a `FitTarget` (G.4) whose `OpticalFunction`/`EllipsometricFunction` matches the measured quantity and whose desiredValue is the measured datum; the resulting `FitTarget list` MUST be handed to the G.5 local-refinement entry point. The regressable model parameters MUST be the G.3 design variables ‚Äî thicknesses, dispersion coefficients (optical constants), and geometry ‚Äî matching 010 ¬ßII.5 ("regress model parameters (thicknesses, optical constants, nonuniformity, roughness)"). Nonuniformity and roughness MUST be expressed, when in scope, as additional `DesignParameter` closures over the base system, NOT as new engine primitives; this part adds no roughness physics beyond what such a closure expresses. This file MUST NOT introduce a measurement-format registry or autodetection beyond the explicit CSV/tab path named here.

### G.8 Fit-quality reporting [Standard]

This part MUST compute and expose fit-quality metrics in a new file `OpticalConstructor.Optimization/FitQuality.fs`, carrying the **[Standard]** tier from 010 ¬ßII.5. From the `OptimizationResult.finalResiduals` (G.1) and the residual Jacobian at the solution, this part MUST compute œá¬≤/MSE, parameter confidence intervals, and the parameter correlation matrix, and MUST retain the per-sample residuals for residual plots and fit-vs-measured overlay (010 ¬ßII.5).

The confidence intervals and correlation matrix MUST be derived from the covariance estimate (inverse of J·µÄJ scaled by reduced œá¬≤). The required real-matrix inverse/factorization MUST go through the Part A math seam `MathNetNumericsMath.fs:5` (this is engine-side linear algebra, NOT optimization, so ALGLIB MUST NOT be used here per ¬ßA.8); the cloned Math.NET routines reached via that seam are the primitive to call. The residual-plot and overlay data MUST be returned as plain arrays for the G.10 UI and the charting path (`plotComparison`, `Charting.fs:38`); this part MUST NOT render charts itself. A `FitReport` (new record) MUST aggregate œá¬≤/MSE, the interval/correlation tables, and the residual arrays, and MUST be persistable as a `.binz` fit-history sidecar (¬ß0 constraint 4; `serialize ‚Ä¶ BinaryZippedFormat`, `Core.fs:257`), NOT inside the canonical JSON project.

### G.9 Needle/tunnelling synthesis and global optimization [Standard]

This part MUST implement synthesis methods in a new file `OpticalConstructor.Optimization/Synthesis.fs`, carrying the **[Standard]** tier from 010 ¬ßII.5. **Needle optimization** MUST, at each iteration, evaluate the merit-function gradient with respect to inserting a vanishingly thin layer at each candidate depth in the films list of the base `OpticalSystem` (`Media.fs:94`), insert one `Layer` (`Media.fs:24`) of small thickness at the position that most decreases the merit function, then re-run local refinement (G.5) on the grown design ‚Äî growing the layer count without bounding the parameter space (010 ¬ßII.5). **Tunnelling / gradual evolution** MUST perturb a converged design to escape local minima and re-refine, combined with needle insertion per 010 ¬ßII.5.

**Global optimization** MUST provide simulated annealing and a genetic/evolutionary algorithm for multimodal merit landscapes where refinement stalls (010 ¬ßII.5). These MUST be driven through the same G.1 `Residual` closure and MUST select the appropriate `OptimizationMethod`/ALGLIB routine through G.2 where one exists; the annealing/GA outer loop that ALGLIB does not provide MAY be implemented in this file as an explicit F# loop over the `Residual` closure, with each candidate evaluated by the G.4 merit assembly. This part MUST NOT add parallel-evaluation infrastructure, distributed execution, or a plugin system for synthesis strategies ‚Äî only the two synthesis families and two global methods named in 010 ¬ßII.5.

### G.10 Synthesis/Fit operator page, jobs, and result refresh

This part MUST add a top-level Synthesis/Fit page to the FuncUI MVU surface (`OpticalConstructor.Ui.fsproj`, Part A assembly map) hosting the G.4 target editor, the G.3 parameter/bound table, the method selector (G.1 `OptimizationMethod`), and the G.8 fit report. Because this introduces an operator page and long-running cancellable jobs, this part MUST commit explicitly on the operator-facing UX checklist:

1. **Discoverability/nav entry** ‚Äî the page MUST be reachable from the main navigation as a named "Synthesis / Fit" entry alongside the existing stack/chart pages.
2. **Progress granularity** ‚Äî every optimizer run MUST report progress as iteration count and current œá¬≤/MSE via a progress channel distinct from the G.1 interface (G.1 stays callback-free); the channel MUST update at each optimizer iteration. The shared background-job runner of Part J ¬ßJ.10 hosts this run; this part supplies the per-iteration progress payload.
3. **Pre-confirmation gate vs one-click** ‚Äî starting a fit MUST be one-click (non-destructive: it produces a candidate system, it does not overwrite saved files); ACCEPTING a fit result that replaces the working `OpticalSystem` MUST require an explicit confirm.
4. **Completion ‚Üí results refresh** ‚Äî on optimizer completion the refined system MUST be folded back via G.3 and the result charts MUST refresh through the existing `plotComparison` path (`Charting.fs:38`) showing fit-vs-measured overlay (G.8) without a manual reload.
5. **Opposing-action button UX + undo** ‚Äî the page MUST provide a Cancel button that cooperatively stops the running optimizer (the G.5/G.9 loops MUST observe a cancellation flag) and a Revert action restoring the pre-fit working system; Cancel and Start MUST NOT be the same control.
6. **Committable file vs root .gitignore collisions** ‚Äî `.binz` fit-history sidecars (G.8) and any exported fit reports MUST be written under the project's working folder and MUST be added to the repository root `.gitignore`, NOT committed; the canonical JSON project (which references them as sidecars, ¬ß0 constraint 4) is the committable artefact.

Long-running execution MUST run off the UI thread so the MVU `update` stays responsive; this part MUST NOT add a job-queue, retry, or scheduling abstraction beyond a single cancellable run at a time.

### G.11 Validation against the Wolfram reference fits

This part MUST validate the ALGLIB `minlm` path against the Wolfram reference fits, per ¬ßA.8 ("Validate ALGLIB's `minlm` against the Wolfram reference fits"), in a new test file `Berreman/BerremanTests/OptimizationTests.fs` added to `BerremanTests.fsproj` (`Berreman.slnx:20`). The tests MUST encode, as fixed expected values, the converged parameters and final œá¬≤ from the ported Wolfram `FindMinimum`/`NonlinearModelFit` runs for at least one thin-film R/T refinement case and one ellipsometric Œ®/Œî case, and MUST assert that `LocalRefinement` (G.5) driving `LevenbergMarquardt` (G.2) reproduces them to a stated tolerance.

The tests MUST exercise the full path ‚Äî `DesignParameter` mapping (G.3) ‚Üí merit residual (G.4) ‚Üí `optimize` (G.1) ‚Üí ALGLIB adapter (G.2) ‚Äî using the real `OpticalSystemSolver` (`Solvers.fs:199`), NOT a stubbed forward model, so the validation covers the engine/optimizer seam end to end. A bounded-parameter case MUST assert that a fit started outside the physical range terminates inside the G.3 bounds (no negative thickness). These tests MUST NOT depend on the UI project.

