## Part H ‚Äî Charts & visualization

### H.0 Problem statement

The Berreman engine already produces every scalar the optical-constructor app needs to chart: reflectance/transmittance and their s/p splits, ellipticity, azimuth, Stokes vectors, and dispersion components are all exposed through `Solution.func` (`FieldFunctions.fs:192`) and the `OpticalFunction` DU (`FieldFunctions.fs:109`), and the engine already ships a Plotly.NET-based plotting surface ‚Äî `plot` (`Charting.fs:21`), `plotComparison` (`Charting.fs:38`), `plot3D` (`Charting.fs:64`), and the dispersion helpers `plotN11`/`plotXi11`/`plotRho11` (`Charting.fs:95,96,105`). Those functions are batch, fire-and-forget renderers: each ends in `Chart.show` (`Charting.fs:34,52,92`) and opens a browser tab. They are unusable as the live, embedded, interactive chart surface an MVU desktop app requires, but they are the authoritative source of the data series and of the axis/legend conventions, and they MUST be reused as the data path rather than re-derived.

This part owns the chart presentation layer of `OpticalConstructor.Ui.fsproj` (Part A assembly layout). Part A fixes the chart technology split: ScottPlot is the fast, native, interactive 2D/contour surface, and Plotly.NET hosted in WebView2 is the publication/export surface. This part SHALL bind those two renderers to the engine's series data, deliver the [Core] interactive 1D plot and [Core] overlay/comparison, the [Standard] 2D/3D surface & contour, [Standard] chart customization, [Standard] cursor/readout & markers, and the [Standard] specialized plots (polarization ellipse, Poincar√© sphere, field-depth profile, CIE chromaticity, n,k dispersion). It does NOT own sweep computation (Part A sweeps seam: `calculate`/`calculate3D`, `Variables.fs:237,270`), nor color/CIE numeric conversion (a net-new calculation owned by Part F ¬ßF.8), nor chart-data CSV/image export (Part I). Part H renders series it is handed and renders the CIE swatch/diagram from XYZ it is handed; it MUST NOT compute the spectra-to-XYZ transform itself.

The chart settings carried in the project (`OpticalConstructorProject` chart-settings field, ¬ßA.7) are the single persisted state for axis ranges, scales, titles, colors, line styles, units, gridlines, annotations, and per-trace visibility. This part defines the F# chart-settings record and the pure projection from it onto each renderer; it MUST NOT introduce a second settings store, a per-chart mutable config object, or a settings-versioning/migration shim.

Specialized plots that have no engine primitive (Poincar√© sphere as a 3D ball, polarization ellipse as a parametric curve, CIE horseshoe) are net-new drawing code, admitted here ONLY because ¬ß6 of 010 names them. The polarization-ellipse and Poincar√©-sphere inputs are existing engine outputs ‚Äî `Ellipticity` (`Fields.fs:302`), `Polarization` azimuth (`Fields.fs:314`), and `StokesVector` from `Solution.stokesR`/`stokesT` (`FieldFunctions.fs:227,238`) ‚Äî and MUST be consumed from there, not recomputed from raw fields.

### H.1 Chart-settings record and per-renderer projection [Standard]

Part H MUST define one immutable F# record `ChartSettings` in a new file `OpticalConstructor.Ui/Charts/ChartSettings.fs`, holding axis ranges (X and Y min/max as `float option`), per-axis scale (a `AxisScale = Linear | Log10` DU), title, legend visibility, gridline visibility, and a per-trace list of `{ functionId : OpticalFunction; name : string; color : string; lineStyle : LineStyle; visible : bool }`. `OpticalFunction` MUST be the engine DU at `FieldFunctions.fs:109` ‚Äî Part H MUST NOT redefine the set of plottable quantities. `ChartSettings` MUST be the field type used by the `OpticalConstructorProject` chart-settings slot defined in ¬ßA.7; this part fills that slot's shape and MUST NOT create a parallel settings container. Two pure functions `applyToScottPlot : ChartSettings -> ScottPlot.Plot -> unit` and `applyToPlotly : ChartSettings -> GenericChart -> GenericChart` MUST live in `ChartSettings.fs` and be the ONLY place axis/legend/grid/trace-visibility settings are pushed to a renderer. Schema versioning, per-chart mutable config objects, and a settings-migration path are OUT OF SCOPE.

### H.2 Series adapter over the engine charting data [Core]

Part H MUST add a new module `OpticalConstructor.Ui/Charts/SeriesData.fs` that converts engine output into renderer-neutral series, reusing the engine's own data extraction rather than the engine's `Chart.show` wrappers. For 1D, it MUST call `Analytics.Variables.calculate` (`Variables.fs:237`) to obtain the `(float * Solution) []` array and project each requested `OpticalFunction` through `Solution.func` (`FieldFunctions.fs:192`), matching the choose-on-`Some` pattern the engine already uses inside `plot` (`Charting.fs:26-30`). For 3D it MUST call `calculate3D` (`Variables.fs:270`) and `Charting.mapFun` (`Charting.fs:57`) to obtain the Z grid. The adapter MUST return `{ name : string; points : (float * float) [] }` for 1D and `{ z : float [] []; xValues : float []; yValues : float [] }` for surfaces. Part H MUST NOT re-implement the solver call or the sweep loop ‚Äî those are the Part A sweeps seam. Caching of computed series is OUT OF SCOPE unless put in scope by the live-recalculation directive in the construction part; Part H consumes whatever series array it is handed.

### H.3 Interactive 1D plot [Core]

Part H MUST render the [Core] interactive 1D plot (R/T/Œ®/Œî vs. Œª or angle, multiple traces, legend, zoom/pan) onto a hosted ScottPlot control in a new file `OpticalConstructor.Ui/Charts/Plot1DView.fs`. Each visible trace from `ChartSettings` (H.1) MUST be drawn from a `SeriesData` 1D series (H.2) via `Plot.Add.Scatter`, named with the engine's `OpticalFunction.info.fullName` so legend labels match the engine convention used at `Charting.fs:31`. Zoom and pan MUST use ScottPlot's built-in interaction (no custom pan/zoom math). The X axis label and its plotted range MUST come from the sweep variable, mirroring `Charting.fs:32` which reads `x.name`, `x.plotMinValue`, `x.plotMaxValue`; where `ChartSettings` overrides the range, the override wins. The view MUST be a pure function of `ChartSettings` plus the series array and MUST hold no mutable chart state of its own.

### H.4 Overlay & comparison of multiple systems [Core]

Part H MUST render the [Core] overlay/comparison view in `Plot1DView.fs` by drawing the same `OpticalFunction` from several systems on one ScottPlot plot, reusing the per-system data layout of `Analytics.Charting.plotComparison` (`Charting.fs:38`) ‚Äî one `calculate` (`Variables.fs:237`) per system, then one trace per (system, function) pair named `fullName + " (" + index + ")"` exactly as `Charting.fs:49`. The set of systems to overlay MUST come from the multi-system workspace owned by Part J (¬ßJ.5); Part H MUST NOT introduce its own system-collection store. A new browser tab MUST NOT be opened ‚Äî `plotComparison`'s terminal `Chart.show` (`Charting.fs:52`) MUST NOT be called from the app; only its series-assembly logic is reused.

### H.5 2D/3D surface & contour plots [Standard]

Part H MUST render the [Standard] 2D/3D surface and contour plot (e.g. R vs. Œª √ó angle) in a new file `OpticalConstructor.Ui/Charts/Plot3DView.fs`. Surface and contour MUST be produced by Plotly.NET hosted in the WebView2 control (Part A chart split), reusing the `Chart.Surface` construction and the axis-swap convention documented in `Analytics.Charting.plot3D` (`Charting.fs:64-82`, including the `kk:20180922` swap of X with Y at `Charting.fs:74-77`) and the contour toggle `Contours.initXyz(Show = true)` at `Charting.fs:75`. The Z grid MUST come from the `SeriesData` surface adapter (H.2) over `calculate3D`/`mapFun`; Part H MUST NOT call the solver directly. Custom OpenTK 3D rendering is reserved by Part A for the system/beam viewport and MUST NOT be used here.

### H.6 Chart customization [Standard]

Part H MUST wire the [Standard] customization controls ‚Äî axis ranges, linear/log scale, titles, colors, line styles, units, gridlines, annotations, and per-trace show/hide ‚Äî to mutate ONLY the `ChartSettings` record (H.1) through the MVU `update`, never the renderer directly. Log scale MUST be the `AxisScale.Log10` case applied through `applyToScottPlot`/`applyToPlotly` (H.1); Part H MUST NOT add a separate log-transform of the data. Unit selection on an axis MUST convert display values at the chart boundary using the boundary-only conversions defined in ¬ßA.10 (eV‚Üînm, cm‚Åª¬π, nm/¬µm/√Ö/mm) ‚Äî the Part D `Units.fs` conversion seam (¬ßD.2); Part H MUST NOT store a non-SI value in `ChartSettings` and MUST NOT re-implement the conversions ‚Äî it calls the ¬ßA.10 functions. Per-trace show/hide MUST flip the `visible` flag on the trace entry, with the projection functions in H.1 omitting hidden traces. Config-file knobs beyond `ChartSettings` and any settings-migration code are OUT OF SCOPE.

### H.7 Cursor/readout & markers [Standard]

Part H MUST add the [Standard] cursor/readout and marker tools in a new file `OpticalConstructor.Ui/Charts/Readout.fs`, operating on the ScottPlot 1D plot (H.3). It MUST provide: hover readout of the nearest series point (ScottPlot `GetNearest`), a peak finder and a min finder over a chosen trace's `(float * float) []` series (pure array scan, returning the extremum point), an FWHM measurement (half-maximum crossing interpolation on one trace), and a two-cursor delta reporting ŒîX and ŒîY between two placed markers. These MUST be pure functions over the `SeriesData` 1D array plus the cursor positions; Part H MUST NOT recompute physics or re-solve to find peaks. No marker state may live outside the MVU model ‚Äî marker positions MUST be fields in the chart page model, not renderer-held state.

### H.8 Polarization ellipse and Poincar√© sphere [Standard]

Part H MUST render the [Standard] polarization-ellipse and Poincar√©-sphere plots in a new file `OpticalConstructor.Ui/Charts/PolarizationPlots.fs`, consuming existing engine outputs only. The polarization ellipse MUST be a parametric curve built from the reflected/transmitted `Ellipticity` (`Fields.fs:302`) and azimuth `Polarization` (`Fields.fs:314`) exposed on `EmFieldSystem` as `ellipticityR`/`ellipticityT`/`azimuthR`/`azimuthT` (`FieldFunctions.fs:157,161,165,169`), drawn on a ScottPlot plot. The Poincar√© sphere MUST be a Plotly.NET 3D sphere (hosted in WebView2) onto which the normalized Stokes vector `(S1,S2,S3)/S0` is plotted as a point, the Stokes vector taken from `Solution.stokesR`/`stokesT` (`FieldFunctions.fs:227,238`) and `StokesVector` (`Fields.fs:580` per ¬ßA). Part H MUST NOT recompute Stokes parameters from raw E/H fields and MUST NOT redefine `StokesVector`.

### H.9 Field-depth profile plot [Standard]

Part H MUST render the [Standard] in-layer field-depth profile (|E|¬≤, Poynting, or absorption vs. depth) in `Plot1DView.fs` as a standard 1D ScottPlot trace, with depth (in meters, converted to the layer's display unit at the boundary per ¬ßA.10) on the X axis. The per-depth field samples MUST come from the field-depth profile owned by Part F ¬ßF.6 (`fieldDepthProfile`, `Analytics/FieldProfile.fs`), which itself samples the engine field-propagation seam `EmField.propagate (s : Layer)` (`BerremanMatrix.fs:224`, the inter-element propagation seam named in ¬ßA); Part H MUST NOT add a new in-layer field solver and MUST NOT re-sample the layer independently of ¬ßF.6. Part H consumes the `(double<meter> * float) list` profile and renders it; the discretization (samples-per-layer count) is the argument ¬ßF.6 already takes.

### H.10 CIE chromaticity diagram [Standard]

Part H MUST render the [Standard] CIE chromaticity diagram in a new file `OpticalConstructor.Ui/Charts/CieView.fs`, drawing the CIE 1931 horseshoe boundary and plotting a supplied chromaticity point (x,y) plus its sRGB swatch. The XYZ‚Üíxy and XYZ‚ÜísRGB numbers, and the spectra‚ÜíXYZ integration, are the net-new color calculation owned by Part F ¬ßF.8 (`spectrumToXyz`/`xyzToLab`/`xyzToSrgb`, `Analytics/Colorimetry.fs`); Part H MUST consume the resulting `{ x : float; y : float; rgb : byte * byte * byte }` and MUST NOT implement the color-matching-function integration or the gamma/sRGB transform itself. The horseshoe boundary spectral-locus coordinates are static reference data and MUST live as a literal array in `CieView.fs`; this is the only static numeric table Part H introduces.

### H.11 n,k dispersion plot [Standard]

Part H MUST render the [Standard] n,k (and œÅ, Œµ-component) dispersion plot in `Plot1DView.fs` by reusing the engine dispersion helpers as the data source: the `plotDispersion` series builder (`Charting.fs:85`) and the named accessors `plotN11`/`plotXi11`/`plotN22`/`plotXi22`/`plotN33`/`plotXi33`/`plotRho11`/`plotRho22`/`plotRho33` (`Charting.fs:95-107`), which compute series from an `OpticalPropertiesWithDisp` over a `Range<WaveLength>`. Part H MUST extract those helpers' series-building bodies into the `SeriesData` adapter (H.2) so they end in renderer-neutral `(float * float) []` instead of the engine's terminal `Chart.show` (`Charting.fs:92`); Part H MUST NOT call `Chart.show` and MUST NOT re-derive the n/k/œÅ formulas, which are owned by `OpticalPropertiesWithDisp` (`Dispersion.fs:53` per ¬ßA).

