## Part I ‚Äî Project management, persistence & I/O

### I.0 Problem statement

The Optical Constructor must persist an entire working session ‚Äî the optical systems, the material library entries, the light sources, the parametric sweeps, the chart settings, the beam tree, and the per-element default units ‚Äî to a file the user can save, reopen, share, hand-edit, and have an LLM edit safely. Per the ¬ß0 binding constraints (rule 4) and Part A, that canonical document is **JSON validated against a published JSON Schema on load**, and zipped FsPickler (`.binz`) is admitted **only** for derived/bulk sidecars (sweep results, field maps, fit histories) referenced from the JSON. This part owns the storage assembly `OpticalConstructor.Storage.fsproj` (declared in Part A's layout), the schema file `optical-constructor-project.schema.json` (anchored in ¬ßA.7), and every read/write seam that touches disk.

The Berreman tree today contains **no file I/O whatsoever** ‚Äî a repository-wide search for `File.`, `WriteAllText`, `StreamWriter`, `refractiveindex`, `.csv`, or `yaml` returns nothing across `C:/GitHub/Berreman/Berreman`. Every directive here is therefore net-new code, and every "reuse" claim points outside the Berreman tree at `Softellect.Sys.Core` (the zipped-binary serializer at `C:/GitHub/Softellect/Sys/Core.fs:254`) or at the new package references Part A admits (System.Text.Json + FSharp.SystemTextJson, FSharp.Data, JsonSchema.Net). The domain root `OpticalConstructorProject` and the schema `$defs` are defined by Part A (¬ßA.7); this part defines the **serialization, validation, file-format, export, history, and library-exchange behaviour** over that root, and MUST NOT redefine the aggregate or its `$defs`.

This part introduces operator-facing actions that are destructive or long-running ‚Äî Open (replaces the in-memory project), Save/Save As, autosave (a background timer that writes to disk), undo/redo (mutates history), and report generation (a long-running render). The Operator-facing UX checklist therefore applies and is discharged explicitly in the directives below: discoverability via the File menu and a recent-files list, progress granularity for report/export, a pre-confirmation gate on Open-over-dirty-project, a completion‚Üírefresh contract, an undo path opposing every destructive edit, and committable-file vs `.gitignore` collisions for autosave/sidecar artefacts.

Scope is the minimum that satisfies the 010 Part II ¬ß7 bullets and Part III ¬ß2 storage decisions. **Schema versioning, migration code, backwards-compatibility shims, multi-format converters, encryption, cloud sync, and error-wrapping retry layers are OUT OF SCOPE** and MUST NOT be introduced; the only error channel is the `Result<'T, 'E>` returned by each IO function (project CLAUDE.md). The canonical SI-meters rule (Part A) is enforced at this boundary: serialization reads/writes the domain model's stored `double<meter>` and `WaveLength.value` (`Fields.fs:284`) verbatim; per-element display units round-trip as a separate `unitOfMeasure` field, never by storing a non-SI number.

### I.1 [Core] ‚Äî Canonical JSON serialization of the project root

`OpticalConstructor.Storage.fsproj` MUST provide a module `OpticalConstructor.Storage.ProjectJson` exposing `serializeProject : OpticalConstructorProject -> Result<string, StorageError>` and `deserializeProject : string -> Result<OpticalConstructorProject, StorageError>` over the Part A root aggregate `OpticalConstructorProject` (¬ßA.7). Serialization MUST use **System.Text.Json with FSharp.SystemTextJson** (the package Part A admits) configured with `JsonFSharpOptions` so that F# records, discriminated unions (`ConstructorElement`, `BeamBranch`, `Substrate`, `Thickness`, `WaveLength`), and `option` values round-trip idiomatically; it MUST NOT use Newtonsoft or FsPickler for this path (binding rule 4).

Reuse before invention: do NOT hand-roll a JSON writer ‚Äî the single primitive to reach for is `System.Text.Json.JsonSerializer.Serialize/Deserialize` with the `FSharp.SystemTextJson` converter registered once in a shared `JsonSerializerOptions` value. The serializer MUST write the domain model's canonical SI fields verbatim: `Thickness of double<meter>` (`Media.fs:12`) and `WaveLength.value : double<meter>` (`Fields.fs:284`) are emitted as their stored meter values; the human-facing unit travels only in the `unitOfMeasure` field (¬ßA.7 `unitOfMeasure` `$def`). No unit conversion, rounding, or canonicalization of physical magnitudes occurs in this module.

`StorageError` MUST be a net-new DU in `OpticalConstructor.Storage.Errors` with cases at minimum `JsonParseError of string`, `SchemaValidationError of string list`, `SchemaMissing`, `FileIoError of exn`, `BinzError of exn`, and `SidecarMissing of string`. It MUST NOT wrap or shadow `Softellect.Sys.Errors`; it is the sole error channel for this part and is returned, never thrown.

### I.2 [Core] ‚Äî Published JSON Schema and validate-on-load

`OpticalConstructor.Storage.fsproj` MUST ship the file `schema/optical-constructor-project.schema.json` as a build-copied content item, carrying `"$id": "https://berreman/schema/optical-constructor-project.json"` and the `$defs` enumerated in ¬ßA.7 (`opticalSystem`, `layer`, `opticalProperties`, `beamNode`, `beamBranch`, `constructorElement`, `materialEntry`, `sourceSpec`, `unitOfMeasure`). This part authors the schema's **top-level envelope and the storage-owned `$defs`** (`materialEntry`, `sourceSpec`, `unitOfMeasure`, and the project root object: `schemaVersion` string, `systems`, `materials`, `sources`, `sweeps`, `chartSettings`, `beamTree`, plus optional `sidecars` array); the physics-shaped `$defs` (`opticalSystem`, `layer`, `opticalProperties`, `beamNode`, `beamBranch`, `constructorElement`) are filled by Parts B‚ÄìG and MUST NOT be re-shaped here.

`deserializeProject` (I.1) MUST validate the parsed JSON document against this schema **before** binding it to `OpticalConstructorProject`, using **JsonSchema.Net** (the package Part A admits) ‚Äî load the schema once into a `JsonSchema` value and call `Evaluate`. On any validation failure the function MUST return `SchemaValidationError` carrying the list of JsonSchema.Net evaluation messages and MUST NOT return a partially-bound project. If the schema content item is absent at runtime the function MUST return `SchemaMissing`. Schema **versioning and migration are out of scope**: a `schemaVersion` whose value does not equal the single shipped version MUST surface as `SchemaValidationError`, not trigger any migration code.

### I.3 [Core] ‚Äî Project file read/write with `.ocproj` extension

`OpticalConstructor.Storage.fsproj` MUST provide `ProjectFile` with `saveProject : string -> OpticalConstructorProject -> Result<unit, StorageError>` and `openProject : string -> Result<OpticalConstructorProject, StorageError>`. `saveProject` MUST serialize via `serializeProject` (I.1) and write the resulting UTF-8 text to the given path with the extension `.ocproj`; `openProject` MUST read the file, then call `deserializeProject` (I.2) so that schema validation always runs on load. All filesystem access MUST be wrapped so any exception becomes `FileIoError`; exceptions MUST NOT propagate out of these functions (project CLAUDE.md, `Result`-not-exceptions).

The canonical project is a single self-contained JSON text file ‚Äî it MUST NOT be a zip, a folder bundle, or a multi-file container. Sidecars (I.4) live beside it as separate `.binz` files referenced by relative path from the JSON's `sidecars` array. `.ocproj` files are user documents and MUST NOT be added to any `.gitignore`; autosave and sidecar artefacts are addressed in I.5 and I.4 respectively. This `openProject` path is the single project-open seam every other part routes template loads and gallery loads through (Part J ¬ßJ.3, ¬ßJ.11).

### I.4 [Core/Standard] ‚Äî `.binz` sidecars for derived/bulk artefacts only

`OpticalConstructor.Storage.fsproj` MUST provide `Sidecar` with `writeSidecar<'T> : string -> 'T -> Result<unit, StorageError>` and `readSidecar<'T> : string -> Result<'T, StorageError>`, used **only** for derived/bulk artefacts: parametric-sweep result tables (the output of `calculate`/`calculate3D`, `Variables.fs:237,270` per Part A), in-layer field maps, and fit/design histories. These functions MUST reuse `Softellect.Sys.Core.serialize`/`deserialize` with `BinaryZippedFormat` (`C:/GitHub/Softellect/Sys/Core.fs:254,257`), and the file extension MUST be `.binz` (`Softellect.Sys.Primitives.fs:267`). Reuse is mandatory: do NOT introduce a second pickler, a second zip path, or a custom binary format ‚Äî the one primitive to reach for is `Softellect.Sys.Core.serialize BinaryZippedFormat`.

`.binz` sidecars MUST NOT carry the canonical project definition or any hand/LLM-editable content (binding rule 4); attempting to serialize `OpticalConstructorProject` through `writeSidecar` is forbidden by directive and MUST NOT be done. Each sidecar is referenced from the project JSON only by **relative path** under the `sidecars` array (I.2); the schema MUST require those paths to be relative so a moved project folder keeps its sidecars. Sidecars are regenerable derived data and SHOULD be excluded from version control: this part's `files` list contributes a `.gitignore` entry for `*.binz` under the project working folder. Caching policies, sidecar eviction, and retention windows are OUT OF SCOPE.

### I.5 [Standard] ‚Äî Recent files and autosave

`OpticalConstructor.Storage.fsproj` MUST provide `RecentFiles` with `loadRecent : unit -> string list` and `pushRecent : string -> string list`, persisting the most-recently-used `.ocproj` paths (most-recent first, bounded list) to a single JSON preferences file in the per-user application-data folder, serialized through `serializeProject`'s shared `JsonSerializerOptions` (I.1) ‚Äî no separate JSON stack. The recent-files list is the discoverability surface required by the Operator-facing UX checklist; the UI (Part J) renders it under File ‚ñ∏ Recent.

`OpticalConstructor.Storage.fsproj` MUST provide `Autosave` with `autosavePath : string -> string` (deriving a sibling `<name>.ocproj.autosave` path) and `writeAutosave : string -> OpticalConstructorProject -> Result<unit, StorageError>`, reusing `serializeProject` (I.1) ‚Äî autosave writes the **same canonical JSON**, never `.binz`. Autosave MUST write to the `.autosave` sidewrite path and MUST NOT overwrite the user's `.ocproj` until the user explicitly Saves; this satisfies the checklist's destructive-action gate by keeping the autosave file distinct from the committed document. The autosave timer interval and trigger are owned by the UI model (Part J ¬ßJ.10); this part owns only the write function and the path derivation. `*.autosave` MUST be contributed to `.gitignore`. Retry-on-failure and rolling autosave generations are OUT OF SCOPE ‚Äî a failed autosave returns `FileIoError` and the UI surfaces it.

### I.6 [Standard] ‚Äî Undo/redo of model edits

`OpticalConstructor.Storage.fsproj` MUST provide `History` with an immutable type `EditHistory` holding `past : OpticalConstructorProject list`, `present : OpticalConstructorProject`, and `future : OpticalConstructorProject list`, plus `push : OpticalConstructorProject -> EditHistory -> EditHistory`, `undo : EditHistory -> EditHistory`, and `redo : EditHistory -> EditHistory`. The structure MUST be immutable F# (project CLAUDE.md) and MUST NOT use `.Value`/`.IsSome`; `undo`/`redo` MUST pattern-match the `past`/`future` lists and MUST be no-ops (return the input unchanged) when the respective list is empty. This satisfies the Operator-facing UX checklist's opposing-action/undo requirement: every destructive model edit in the UI pushes onto `EditHistory`, and `undo` is its inverse. This is the multi-level undo/redo history that Part B ¬ßB.10 defers here; the construction page's single-level snapshot swap is the degenerate one-deep case.

Undo/redo holds **whole-project snapshots** in memory; persistent on-disk undo journals, command-pattern diff logs, and bounded-history eviction are OUT OF SCOPE for this directive (the design-history file in I.8 is the durable record). The history depth bound, if any, is owned by the UI model (Part J).

### I.7 [Standard] ‚Äî Chart-data and chart-image export

`OpticalConstructor.Storage.fsproj` MUST provide `Export` with `exportCsv : string -> (string list * float[][]) -> Result<unit, StorageError>` writing sweep results as comma-separated rows (header row of column names, then numeric rows) and `exportExcel : string -> (string list * float[][]) -> Result<unit, StorageError>` writing an `.xlsx` workbook. The CSV column data MUST be the same sweep tuples produced by the engine's `calculate`/`calculate3D` (`Variables.fs:237,270` per Part A) and rendered to charts by `plot`/`plotComparison`/`plot3D` (`Charting.fs:21,38,64`); this part serializes that already-computed data and MUST NOT re-run or re-implement the solver. Excel export MUST use the existing in-tree XLSX dependency if one is referenced by `Analytics.fsproj`; if none is, ClosedXML MUST be added as the single Excel package reference (no new Excel abstraction layer).

Chart **image** export to PNG/SVG/PDF MUST be delegated to the chart libraries Part A names, not re-implemented: Plotly.NET charts (the engine's `Charting.fs` path, `Chart.show` at `Charting.fs:34`) export through Plotly.NET's image writer hosted in WebView2 (Part A UI stack), and ScottPlot charts export through ScottPlot's own `SavePng`/`SaveSvg`. `Export` MUST expose `exportChartImage : string -> ChartImageFormat -> ChartHandle -> Result<unit, StorageError>` where `ChartImageFormat = Png | Svg | Pdf` is a net-new DU and `ChartHandle` is the UI-supplied chart object; this function dispatches to the owning library's save call and MUST NOT rasterize or vectorize charts itself. The Operator-facing UX checklist's progress/completion contract for export: each `export*` function returns `Result` on completion, and the UI refreshes the results pane and offers "Open containing folder" on `Ok`.

### I.8 [Standard] ‚Äî Report generator, material library import/export, design history & diff

`OpticalConstructor.Storage.fsproj` MUST provide `Report.generate : ReportFormat -> OpticalConstructorProject -> ChartHandle list -> Result<unit, StorageError>` producing a single PDF or HTML document (`ReportFormat = Pdf | Html`, net-new DU) containing the stack schematic, the project parameters read from `OpticalConstructorProject` (¬ßA.7), the supplied chart images (via I.7's `exportChartImage`), and any fit-result summary present on the project. HTML report assembly MUST reuse the engine's existing Giraffe.ViewEngine usage (`Charting.fs:9` imports `Giraffe.ViewEngine`; `createDescription` builds `h1`/`h2` nodes at `Charting.fs:13`) rather than introducing a second HTML builder; PDF output MUST be produced by printing that HTML through the same Plotly/WebView2 PDF path used in I.7. The report render is the long-running action in this part: `generate` returns `Result` on completion and the UI (Part J) shows determinate progress per included chart and refreshes to offer the produced file.

`OpticalConstructor.Storage.fsproj` MUST provide `MaterialLibrary` with `importMaterials : string -> Result<MaterialEntry list, StorageError>` and `exportMaterials : string -> MaterialEntry list -> Result<unit, StorageError>` over the ¬ßA.7 `materialEntry` `$def`. Export MUST write the canonical JSON (validated against the `materialEntry` `$def`, I.2) so a library file is itself schema-checked. Import MUST accept that same JSON **and** refractiveindex.info-style external tabulated/CSV data via **FSharp.Data** (the package Part A admits) ‚Äî FSharp.Data is the single primitive to reach for parsing external CSV/measurement data; do NOT hand-roll a CSV reader. Imported n,k tables map onto the engine's dispersion types (`OpticalPropertiesWithDisp`, `Dispersion.fs:53` per Part A) ‚Äî the mapping rules are owned by Part D (¬ßD.9) and MUST NOT be redefined here; this part owns only the file read and the `MaterialEntry list` boundary. This is the shareable material-library file format that Part D ¬ßD.8 defers here.

`OpticalConstructor.Storage.fsproj` MUST provide `DesignHistory` with `appendRevision : string -> OpticalConstructorProject -> Result<unit, StorageError>` and `diffRevisions : OpticalConstructorProject -> OpticalConstructorProject -> ProjectDiff` (net-new `ProjectDiff` record listing added/removed/changed systems, layers, materials, and sources by stable identity). `appendRevision` MUST persist each revision as a numbered canonical-JSON snapshot under a `history/` folder beside the `.ocproj`, reusing `serializeProject` (I.1) ‚Äî revisions are JSON, not `.binz`, because they remain hand/LLM-readable (binding rule 4). `diffRevisions` MUST be a pure F# function comparing two already-loaded project values and MUST NOT shell out to git or any external VCS. Full branching/merge version control is OUT OF SCOPE; the committed scope is append-only revision snapshots plus structural diff, matching 010 ¬ß7's "design history & diff" [Standard] bullet.

---

## Part J ‚Äî Environment, UX shell, schematic view, persistent customization & onboarding

### J.0 Problem statement

The Berreman engine is a headless numerical core: it solves `OpticalSystemSolver` (`Solvers.fs:199`) and renders results through Plotly.NET helpers in `Analytics/Charting.fs`, but it has no application shell, no persistent user environment, and no on-screen representation of a stack as a physical cross-section. Part J owns the **UX shell and environment layer** of the Optical Constructor: the visible surfaces a user touches that are not the beam-tree editor itself (Part B), not the materials/source editors (Parts D/E), and not the charts (Part H). Concretely, Part J owns the schematic cross-section drawing of a stack, the repeat/period unit-cell builder, the stack templates/wizards, drag-and-drop of library items onto layers, the multi-system comparison workspace, the persistent favorites board / recent-files / panel-layout customization, the preferences surface, theme and dockable panels, input validation and physical-sanity warnings, the long-running-job progress/cancel mechanism, and the in-app help/glossary/onboarding gallery.

This part builds strictly on the Part A cross-cutting contract and MUST NOT redefine any name it owns. It consumes the canonical domain types (`OpticalSystem` `Media.fs:94`, `Layer` `Media.fs:24`, `Thickness` `Media.fs:12`, `Substrate` `Media.fs:40`, `WaveLength` `Fields.fs:280`), the net-new orchestration types (`OpticalConstructorProject`, `ConstructorElement`, `BeamTree`/`BeamNode` from ¬ßA.4/¬ßA.7), the canonical-units rule (¬ßA.3, meters internally; eV/cm‚Åª¬π/nm/¬µm/√Ö only at the boundary), the JSON-canonical / `.binz`-derived storage split (¬ßA.7), and the FuncUI audit + undecided-linking gate (¬ßA.5/¬ßA.6/¬ßA.9). The MVU shape (owned model, pure `update`, view as a pure function) from Part III ¬ß3 of 010 is the governing UI architecture and is itself established in Part A ¬ßA.6; Part J adds pages, panels, and the shell that hosts the other parts' surfaces, all inside `OpticalConstructor.Ui.fsproj` (¬ßA.1 assembly layout).

Three subsystems in this part are mostly UI/plumbing over capabilities the engine already has and MUST reuse them rather than reinventing: the schematic view reads `Layer.thickness` / `Substrate` / `IncidentLightInfo` and draws them to scale; the repeat/period builder produces a plain `List<Layer>` for `OpticalSystem.films` (`Media.fs:98`) with no new domain type; the templates/wizards pre-populate an `OpticalConstructorProject` and then hand off to the ordinary editors. Two subsystems are net-new with no engine equivalent and are admitted because 010 Part II ¬ß1/¬ß8 names them explicitly: the **persistent UI-customization store** (favorites board, recent files, panel layout, preferences) and the **long-running-job progress/cancel harness**. Everything net-new here is persisted through Part A's storage seams (Part I): preferences and the favorites board as JSON validated against the project schema family (¬ßA.7), never as FsPickler.

Part J is the shell that introduces top-level operator pages (the workspace, the preferences page) and a long-running, cancellable background job surface; the operator-facing UX checklist is therefore in force and is discharged explicitly in J.10.

### J.1 Schematic cross-section view [Core]

The Ui project MUST provide a `Schematic` module (new file `OpticalConstructor.Ui/Schematic.fs`) that renders a single `OpticalSystem` (`Media.fs:94`) as a vertical, drawn-to-scale cross-section on an Avalonia `Canvas`, color-coded by material, with per-layer thickness labels and the incident-light ray drawn at its angle. The renderer MUST read its geometry only from the canonical domain values and MUST NOT introduce a parallel geometry model:

1. The film stack MUST be drawn from `OpticalSystem.films : List<Layer>` (`Media.fs:98`) top-to-bottom in list order; each band's drawn height MUST be a monotonic function of that layer's `Thickness` (`Media.fs:12`), where `Thickness.Thickness d` carries `d : double<meter>` and `Thickness.Infinity` (the half-space case) MUST be drawn as a fixed-height "semi-infinite" band, not scaled.
2. Thickness labels MUST be formatted in the layer's per-element default unit (the `unitOfMeasure` carried by the project per ¬ßA.7), converting from the stored `double<meter>` to the display unit ONLY here at the view boundary (¬ßA.3) using the Part D `Units.fs` conversion seam (¬ßD.2) over the engine constants `nmToMeter`/`mkmToMeter`/`mmToMeter` (`Constants.fs:27,30,33`); √Ö and eV/cm‚Åª¬π conversions reuse the same ¬ßA.10 boundary helpers. No converted value MAY be written back into the model.
3. The upper and lower half-spaces MUST be drawn from `OpticalSystem.upper` / `OpticalSystem.lower : OpticalProperties` (`Media.fs:97,100`) as labelled incident/exit medium bands.
4. When `OpticalSystem.substrate` is `Some (Substrate.Plate _ | Substrate.Wedge _)` (`Media.fs:99`, `Substrate` `Media.fs:40`), the substrate MUST be drawn as a distinct band; for `Substrate.Wedge w` the band MUST be drawn with a non-parallel lower edge whose slope is taken from the wedge's `WedgeAngle` (`Fields.fs:328`, reached via `w.angle`), making the wedge visually distinct from a plate.
5. The incident-light ray MUST be drawn as a line entering the upper medium at the angle from the active source's `IncidentLightInfo.incidenceAngle` (`Fields.fs:342`); the ray's reflected and transmitted continuations MUST be indicated at the top film interface only (full per-interface beam tracing is owned by Part B's beam tree and MUST NOT be re-derived here).
6. Material color MUST be assigned by a deterministic, pure function of a material's stable identity key (the `materialEntry` id from ¬ßA.7), so the same material is the same color across redraws; the color table is a static map in `Schematic.fs` and MUST NOT be a config knob.

Caching of rendered geometry, retained-mode scene graphs, and an abstraction over the drawing backend are OUT OF SCOPE; the view MUST be a pure `OpticalSystem -> Avalonia control` projection re-evaluated by the MVU `view` (Part A ¬ßA.6 / 010 Part III ¬ß3).

### J.2 Repeat / period unit-cell builder [Standard]

The Ui project MUST provide a `RepeatBuilder` module (new file `OpticalConstructor.Ui/RepeatBuilder.fs`) that lets the user define a unit cell as an ordered list of `Layer` values (`Media.fs:24`) and a positive integer repeat count, and expands it into a flat `List<Layer>` suitable for assignment to `OpticalSystem.films` (`Media.fs:98`). The expansion MUST be the pure function `expand : Layer list -> int -> Layer list` implemented as `List.replicate count cell |> List.concat`; it MUST NOT introduce a new "super-layer" or "period" domain type, and the expanded films MUST be ordinary `Layer` records indistinguishable from manually entered ones. The builder is the [Standard] DBR/Bragg/EUV-Mo‚ÄìSi convenience from 010 Part II ¬ß1; it MUST reject a repeat count `< 1` through the J.9 validation seam rather than silently clamping. Storing the unfactored period as a separate serialized structure is OUT OF SCOPE ‚Äî the project persists only the expanded `films` per ¬ßA.7.

### J.3 Stack templates & wizards [Standard]

The Ui project MUST provide a `Templates` module (new file `OpticalConstructor.Ui/Templates.fs`) exposing a fixed, code-defined set of starting designs ‚Äî AR coating, bandpass filter, beam splitter, polarizer, waveplate, DBR ‚Äî each a pure function `unit -> OpticalConstructorProject` (the root aggregate from ¬ßA.7) that pre-populates a starting design and is then handed to the ordinary editors. Each template MUST build its stack from real `Layer`/`OpticalSystem` values (`Media.fs:24,94`) and, where it needs a periodic structure (DBR), MUST call `RepeatBuilder.expand` (J.2) rather than duplicating that logic. Templates MUST NOT read from disk, MUST NOT be user-editable template files, and MUST NOT introduce a template-definition schema ‚Äî they are F# literals. Loading a template MUST go through the same project-open path as a normal project (Part I ¬ßI.3 `openProject`) so schema validation (¬ßA.7) applies uniformly.

### J.4 Drag-and-drop of library items onto layers [Standard]

The Ui project MUST wire Avalonia drag-and-drop so a material from the materials library panel (Part D) dropped onto a layer row replaces that layer's `Layer.properties : OpticalProperties` (`Media.fs:26`) with the dragged material's resolved `OpticalProperties` (`MaterialProperties.fs:165`), leaving `Layer.thickness` unchanged. The drop payload MUST carry only the stable `materialEntry` id (¬ßA.7), and resolution to `OpticalProperties` MUST go through Part D's material-resolution function ‚Äî Part J MUST NOT re-resolve dispersion models or rebuild tensors. The drop MUST emit a single MVU message that the owning `update` applies immutably (producing a new `Layer`), consistent with the Part A MVU contract; no in-place mutation of the model is permitted (¬ß0 constraint 1, immutable structures).

### J.5 Multi-system comparison workspace [Standard]

The Ui project MUST provide a `Workspace` module (new file `OpticalConstructor.Ui/Workspace.fs`) that holds several `OpticalSystem` values side by side for comparison, each addressed by the project's system collection (`OpticalConstructorProject.systems`, ¬ßA.7). For overlaying their computed curves the workspace MUST call the engine's existing comparison plot `plotComparison` (`Charting.fs:38`) ‚Äî surfaced through the Part H ¬ßH.4 ScottPlot overlay rather than the engine's terminal `Chart.show` ‚Äî which already accepts a `list<FixedInfo>` and plots model-by-model; Part J MUST NOT implement its own multi-curve overlay. The workspace owns layout and selection state only (which systems are visible, which is active); the actual chart surface is Part H's. Holding more than the systems already present in the open `OpticalConstructorProject` ‚Äî e.g. a separate comparison document format ‚Äî is OUT OF SCOPE.

### J.6 Persistent UI-customization & favorites board [Core]

The Ui project MUST provide a `UserEnvironment` module (new file `OpticalConstructor.Ui/UserEnvironment.fs`) defining an `EnvironmentSettings` record that persists the user's working environment between sessions and serves as defaults for new projects. It MUST hold: a **favorites board** (named, grouped pins of frequently used `Layer`s, `materialEntry` ids, `sourceSpec` ids, and whole sub-assemblies expressed as `OpticalSystem` fragments, all referencing ¬ßA.7 shapes), the **last working folder(s)** and an ordered **recent files/projects** list, the **window/panel layout** (J.8), the **toolbar contents**, and the **preferences** (J.7). This is the net-new persistent customization from 010 Part II ¬ß1.

1. `EnvironmentSettings` MUST be persisted as JSON validated on load against a new schema `optical-constructor-environment.schema.json` (added to the ¬ßA.7 schema family, same validation library `JsonSchema.Net` named in ¬ßA.7) ‚Äî NOT as FsPickler/`.binz`, because it is hand/LLM-inspectable user config (¬ßA.7). The serialization MUST reuse the Part I `serializeProject` shared `JsonSerializerOptions` (¬ßI.1) rather than a second JSON stack.
2. The file MUST live at a single fixed per-user path under the OS application-data directory; the resolved path MUST be a committable-vs-gitignore non-issue because it is outside the repository working tree (J.10 checklist item 6). Sub-assemblies pinned on the favorites board MUST be stored by value as `opticalSystem` JSON fragments (¬ßA.7), so a pinned favorite survives even if the project it came from is deleted.
3. Sweep/field-map and other bulk artefacts MUST NOT be embedded in `EnvironmentSettings`; only references (paths/ids) MAY appear, consistent with the `.binz`-sidecar rule (¬ßA.7). Schema versioning and migration of this file are OUT OF SCOPE (¬ß0 constraint 6); on a schema-validation failure the app MUST fall back to built-in defaults rather than attempt migration.

### J.7 Preferences [Standard]

The Ui project MUST provide a `Preferences` record (in `OpticalConstructor.Ui/UserEnvironment.fs`, J.6) carrying: default units (a per-quantity `unitOfMeasure`, ¬ßA.7), default wavelength range, default number of sweep points, decimal display precision, and solver defaults. Solver defaults MUST be expressed as the engine's own `SolverParameters` (`Solvers.fs:15`, whose `numberOfReflections` is the convergence control named in 010 Part II ¬ß4/¬ß8) ‚Äî Part J MUST NOT define a parallel solver-config record. Default-unit and wavelength-range preferences are display/boundary concerns and MUST be applied only at the UI/IO boundary (¬ßA.3); they MUST NOT change how any value is stored. Preferences persist as part of `EnvironmentSettings` (J.6) and are therefore JSON, not `.binz`.

### J.8 Theme & dockable panels [Standard]

The Ui project MUST provide an `AppShell` module (new file `OpticalConstructor.Ui/AppShell.fs`) hosting dockable/resizable panels (stack, materials, sources, chart, results) with saved layouts, and a light/dark theme plus configurable chart color palettes. The theme selection and the serialized panel layout MUST be fields of `EnvironmentSettings` (J.6) and MUST round-trip through its JSON. Chart color palettes MUST be surfaced to Part H but MUST NOT be re-implemented as a charting engine here. The dockable-panel mechanism MUST use Avalonia's docking facilities through the FuncUI clone ‚Äî and therefore MUST NOT be referenced, linked, or built until the mandatory FuncUI-clone audit (¬ßA.6/¬ßA.9 / 010 Part III ¬ß3) has passed and the clone is cleared. **The clone's linking mechanism (local NuGet package OR project reference) is deliberately undecided and MUST remain undecided here; Part J MUST NOT resolve it.** Until the audit passes, `AppShell` MUST be authored against the FuncUI DSL surface as source but MUST NOT add the clone as a dependency.

### J.9 Input validation & physical-sanity warnings [Standard]

The Ui project MUST provide a `Validation` module (new file `OpticalConstructor.Ui/Validation.fs`) exposing pure validators returning `Result<'T, ValidationError list>` (¬ß0 error-handling rule ‚Äî `Result`, not exceptions) for every editable boundary field. It MUST enforce at minimum: thickness `> 0` for finite films (rejecting `Thickness.Thickness d` with `d <= 0.0<meter>`, `Media.fs:12`), repeat count `>= 1` (J.2), a non-empty wavelength range with positive endpoints, and the physical-sanity warnings named in 010 Part II ¬ß8 (e.g. an absorbing region flagged where the imaginary index implies gain, non-causal tabulated data). Validation MUST run at the UI boundary before a value is committed to the model and MUST surface failures inline next to the field; it MUST NOT throw, and it MUST NOT silently coerce out-of-range input. Validators MUST operate on already-parsed values and MUST NOT duplicate unit conversion ‚Äî they receive canonical `double<meter>` etc. after the ¬ßA.3 boundary conversion.

### J.10 Long-running job progress, cancellation & timing [Standard]

The Ui project MUST provide a `JobRunner` module (new file `OpticalConstructor.Ui/JobRunner.fs`) that runs heavy sweeps and optimizations (the engine calls `calculate`/`calculate3D` `Variables.fs:237,270` for sweeps, and Part G's ALGLIB path for fits) on a background worker with progress, cancellation, and elapsed-time reporting, surfaced as MVU messages. This is the single shared background-job harness; Part G ¬ßG.10 supplies the per-iteration optimizer progress payload to it. Because this introduces a long-running, cancellable background job, the operator-facing UX checklist is discharged here:

1. **Discoverability/nav entry.** Every long job MUST be launched from a labelled control on its owning page (the sweep panel, the fit panel), and an active job MUST appear in a single shared status area in `AppShell` (J.8) so it is discoverable regardless of which panel started it.
2. **Progress granularity.** Progress MUST be reported as completed-points-over-total for sweeps (driven by the `RangedVariable` point count, `Variables.fs:42`) and as iteration count for optimization; a job whose total is unknown MUST show an indeterminate-but-running state, never a frozen UI.
3. **Pre-confirmation vs one-click.** Starting a sweep/fit MUST be one-click (it is non-destructive and recomputable). Cancellation, by contrast, MUST be immediate one-click with no confirmation, since the partial result is discardable.
4. **Completion ‚Üí results refresh.** On job completion the runner MUST emit a completion message that triggers the owning page's results/chart refresh through the normal MVU `update` ‚Üí `view` cycle; results MUST NOT require a manual reload.
5. **Opposing-action button + undo.** The Start control MUST become a Cancel control for the duration of the job (single button, two states) so the opposing action is unambiguous; cancelling MUST leave the prior committed results untouched (the cancelled job's partial output is dropped, which is the natural undo).
6. **Committable file vs .gitignore.** Any derived artefact a job writes (sweep/field-map `.binz` sidecars, fit histories) MUST be written under the project's sidecar directory referenced from the project JSON (¬ßA.7), NOT into the repository root; these are derived outputs and Part J MUST NOT add them as committable project files.

Cancellation MUST be cooperative via a `System.Threading.CancellationToken` checked between sweep points / optimizer iterations; killing threads, retry-on-failure loops, and a job queue/scheduler abstraction are OUT OF SCOPE (¬ß0 constraint 6) ‚Äî one job per worker, cancel-and-restart is the model.

### J.11 In-app help, glossary & onboarding gallery [Standard]

The Ui project MUST provide a `Help` module (new file `OpticalConstructor.Ui/Help.fs`) delivering: an in-app material/units glossary and field tooltips, plus a gallery of worked examples and getting-started sample projects shipped with the app. The gallery MUST be built from the engine's existing example scripts in `C:/GitHub/Berreman/Berreman/Analytics/Examples/` ‚Äî at minimum the AR/multilayer, DBR/EUV Mo-Si, active-crystal, wedge, and dispersive-glass cases, which exist as `MultilayerThinFilm.fsx`, `MultilayerThinFilm_EUV.fsx`, `ActiveCrystal.fsx`, `Wedge_Glass.fsx`/`Wedge_BiaxialCrystal.fsx`, and `Glass_Dispersive.fsx` respectively. Each gallery entry MUST open as a normal `OpticalConstructorProject` through the Part I open path (¬ßI.3 `openProject`, so schema validation applies, ¬ßA.7) ‚Äî the `.fsx` files are the design reference for the equivalent shipped sample projects and MUST NOT be executed at runtime by the app. The units glossary MUST state the canonical boundary conversions from ¬ßA.10 (eV via `E[eV] = 1239.84 / Œª[nm]`, cm‚Åª¬π via wavenumber) and MUST NOT introduce a second conversion implementation. Tooltips are static strings co-located in `Help.fs`; an authorable/markdown help-content pipeline is OUT OF SCOPE.

### J.12 2D/3D rendered view of the element/system with the beam path [Standard]

The Ui project MUST provide a `SystemView3D` module (new file `OpticalConstructor.Ui/SystemView3D.fs`) that delivers 010 ¬ß1's [Standard] "2D/3D rendered view of the element/system with the beam path" (010 line 127), rendered in the custom OpenTK 3D viewport Part A reserves for exactly this surface in the `OpticalConstructor.Ui.fsproj` row (¬ßA.1, ¬ßA.6) ‚Äî this is the part that consumes that reservation. The view MUST draw, to scale, the placed `ConstructorElement`s of the open project's `BeamTree`/`BeamNode` topology (¬ßA.4) ‚Äî sample, mirror, lens, polarizer, analyzer, detector ‚Äî positioned along the beam path, and MUST draw the beam path itself as the reflected/transmitted ray segments routed by the beam tree, reading each segment's direction from the solved `EmFieldSystem.reflected`/`.transmitted` (`Fields.fs:553-554`) that Part B already produces (¬ßB.1, ¬ßB.4). This part MUST NOT re-solve the system or re-derive beam routing: it consumes the already-solved beam tree and renders it. Geometry MUST read canonical SI (meters) from the domain values and convert to viewport coordinates only at the render boundary (¬ßA.3); no converted value MAY be written back into the model.

The OpenTK renderer here is distinct from, and MUST NOT duplicate, two existing surfaces: the [Core] 2D schematic cross-section of a single stack (¬ßJ.1, an Avalonia `Canvas`) and the Poincar√©-sphere OpenTK use named for the polarization picker/charts (¬ßE.4, ¬ßH.8). This `SystemView3D` is the system/beam viewport; ¬ßH.8's Poincar√© rendering and ¬ßH.5's reservation note ("Custom OpenTK 3D rendering is reserved by Part A for the system/beam viewport and MUST NOT be used here") both refer to this same reserved viewport, now delivered here. This part MUST NOT add full 3D vector wave optics, diffraction rendering, or a second physics engine (Part A ¬ßA.5); the rendered beam segments are the straight ray/beam paths the orchestration already carries. A retained-mode scene-graph abstraction, level-of-detail, and camera-state persistence beyond the ¬ßJ.6 panel-layout fields are OUT OF SCOPE.

---

## Acceptance criteria

### Part A acceptance

- AC-A1: After the five new projects are added and `Berreman.slnx` is built with the documented MSBuild invocation at Configuration=Release Platform=x64, the solution MUST compile with all five `OpticalConstructor.*` projects and the existing Berreman/Analytics projects in one pass, with no new C# project introduced.
- AC-A2: After loading any canonical project file, the storage layer MUST validate it against `optical-constructor-project.schema.json` (anchors opticalSystem/layer/opticalProperties/beamNode/beamBranch/constructorElement) and MUST reject an invalid file before the domain model is admitted, within the load call.
- AC-A3: After a non-mirror `BeamNode` is solved, the orchestration MUST expose exactly two outgoing beams sourced from `EmFieldSystem.reflected` and `.transmitted` (Fields.fs:553-554) via `OpticalSystemSolver` (Solvers.fs:199), with no parallel solver invoked.
- AC-A4: After a child is attached to the `Transmitted` branch of a mirror `BeamNode`, the construction MUST reject the attachment, leaving the mirror with at most one child on `Reflected`.
- AC-A5: After any physical quantity is stored in the domain model or serialized to canonical JSON, the stored value MUST be in the SI base (meters for length; wavelength reduced via WaveLength.value, Fields.fs:284), with unit conversion occurring only at the UI/IO boundary.
- AC-A6: After a derived/bulk artefact (sweep, field map, fit history) is persisted, it MUST be written via Softellect.Sys.Core.serialize with BinaryZippedFormat to a `.binz` sidecar (Core.fs:257, Primitives.fs:267) referenced by path from the JSON, and the canonical project definition MUST NOT be FsPickler-serialized.
- AC-A7: After an eV or cm‚Åª¬π value is entered at the UI/IO boundary, the boundary conversion MUST round-trip to wavelength-in-meters using E[eV]=1239.84/Œª[nm] without persisting eV or cm‚Åª¬π in the model.
- AC-A8: Before `OpticalConstructor.Ui` is linked against `C:\GitHub\Avalonia.FuncUI.Clone\`, the audit gate MUST be recorded as passed; until then the UI project MUST contain no reference to the clone and the linking-mechanism choice MUST remain unresolved.

### Part B acceptance

- AC-B1: After a `BeamNode` is solved on the construction page, the orchestration layer MUST obtain its `reflected` and `transmitted` outputs by calling the reused `OpticalSystemSolver` (`Solvers.fs:199`) and reading `Solution.emSys` (`Solvers.fs:156`), with no forked or shadowed copy of the solver in `OpticalConstructor.Domain.fsproj`.
- AC-B2: After attaching a child to a non-mirror node, the `BeamTree` MUST permit both a `Reflected` and a `Transmitted` child keyed by `BeamBranch`, and a linear chain MUST be representable as single-child-per-node within one edit action.
- AC-B3: After attempting to attach a `Transmitted` child to a mirror node, `BeamNode.attach` MUST return a `Result.Error` (a `BeamTreeError`) and MUST NOT add the child, while a `Reflected` child attach on the same mirror MUST succeed.
- AC-B4: After a child node is attached on branch `b`, the child MUST be solved from the parent's branch-`b` `EmField` advanced through the reused `EmField.propagate` seam (`BerremanMatrix.fs:224`) via `BaseOpticalSystemSolver(emf, system)` (`Solvers.fs:149`), with no separate Jones/Stokes accumulator introduced.
- AC-B5: After add/delete/reorder/duplicate/group on a layer row, the editor MUST yield a new `OpticalSystem` whose `films : List<Layer>` (`Media.fs:98`) reflects the change with the engine `Layer`/`OpticalSystem` records unmutated.
- AC-B6: After choosing an incident or exit medium, the edited `OpticalSystem`'s `upper`/`lower` `OpticalProperties` (`Media.fs:97,100`) MUST be set to the resolved tensor value, preserving `films` and `substrate`.
- AC-B7: After the substrate switch is set to thin film / plate / wedge, `OpticalSystem.substrate` (`Media.fs:99`) MUST become `None` / `Some (Plate _)` / `Some (Wedge _)` respectively, and re-solving MUST route through the existing `OpticalSystemSolver` substrate branch (`Solvers.fs:201-230`) unchanged.
- AC-B8: After an element/layer/source is created, it MUST carry a per-element default-unit hook (`unitOfMeasure`), and changing that hook MUST NOT alter any stored SI value (thickness in meters per `Constants.fs:6`; wavelength via `WaveLength.value`, `Fields.fs:284`).
- AC-B9: After saving a project, the beam tree and its systems MUST round-trip through the JSON-canonical `OpticalConstructorProject` validated against `optical-constructor-project.schema.json`, and MUST NOT be written via FsPickler/`.binz`.
- AC-B10: After deleting a beam node that has attached children, the construction page MUST present a pre-confirmation gate stating the live-derived descendant count, and after any structural edit the dependent schematic/results views MUST refresh from the new `EmFieldSystem` without a manual reload.
- AC-B11: After `discretize gradientLayer` is called with `subLayerCount = n >= 1`, it MUST return exactly `n` ordinary `Layer` records (`Media.fs:24`) whose `Thickness.Thickness` sum equals `totalThickness` in `double<meter>` and whose `OpticalProperties` are sampled from `indexProfile` at each sub-layer mid-depth, the list being assignable to `OpticalSystem.films` with no gradient-specific engine type and no profile stored in the canonical JSON.

### Part C acceptance

- AC-C1: After a `CurvedSurface` is constructed with radius/aperture entered in nm, ¬µm, and mm, its stored `radiusOfCurvature` and `semiAperture` MUST be in `double<meter>` (Constants.fs:6) with values matching the `nmToMeter`/`mkmToMeter`/`mmToMeter` conversions (Constants.fs:27,30,33), with no non-SI value left in the domain record.
- AC-C2: After `sampleZones surface n` is called for any `n >= 1`, it MUST return exactly `n` `LocalZone`s uniformly spaced in aperture radius from 0 to `semiAperture`, the axis zone (radialPosition = 0) having `localAoiShift = Angle.zero`.
- AC-C3: After `solveZone info zone parameters` runs, the local incident angle fed to `OpticalSystemSolver` (Solvers.fs:199) MUST equal `info.incidenceAngle` shifted by `zone.localAoiShift` via `IncidentLightInfo.rotateY` (Fields.fs:411), and the result MUST be a `Solution` carrying the engine reflected/transmitted split (Solvers.fs:156).
- AC-C4: After `attachCurvedElement` is applied to a `ConstructorElement.CurvedMirror`, every zone `BeamNode` MUST expose a `BeamBranch.Reflected` child and MUST NOT expose a `BeamBranch.Transmitted` child; for a `ConstructorElement.Lens`, every zone node MUST expose both branches.
- AC-C5: After a concave surface is built, its `radiusOfCurvature` MUST be negative and a convex surface positive, with no override flag present; the same surface evaluated through `sag` (C.2) MUST return the correct signed height.
- AC-C6: After `gradeCoating surface zone` runs on a depth-graded EUV mirror, each finite `Thickness.Thickness d` (Media.fs:12) in the returned coating MUST be the original scaled by the zone factor (per the ~5% center-to-edge default) while every `Thickness.Infinity` is unchanged, all values remaining `double<meter>`.
- AC-C7: After a beam crosses an inter-element gap, propagation MUST be performed by `EmField.propagate` (BerremanMatrix.fs:224) over a `Layer` (Media.fs:24) whose thickness is the axial separation in meters, with no second propagation routine introduced.
- AC-C8: After a curved element with grading disabled is sampled into N zones, all N zones MUST share one immutable `OpticalSystem` coating instance (Media.fs:94) with no thickness rescale applied.

### Part D acceptance

- AC-D1: After a user enters a wavelength as `13.5` with default unit `ElectronVolt`, `toWaveLength ElectronVolt 13.5` MUST return a `WaveLength` whose `.value` equals `(1239.84/13.5)` nm reduced through `nmToMeter` (i.e. ‚âà 9.184e-8 m) within 1e-15 m.
- AC-D2: After converting any length value to meters and back through `toMeters`/`fromMeters` for each of Meter/Millimeter/Micrometer/Nanometer/Angstrom, the round-tripped scalar MUST equal the original within 1e-12 relative error, using the `Constants.fs` factors (no re-derived literals).
- AC-D3: After loading a refractiveindex.info YAML page tabulated in ¬µm via `importRefractiveIndexInfo`, the resulting `MaterialEntry.OpticalPropertiesWithDisp.getEps` evaluated at a sampled wavelength MUST equal the engine's value for the same n,k within 1e-9, with the wavelength reduced to meters at import.
- AC-D4: After selecting `evaluate` on a `Sellmeier` model whose coefficients match `Silicon`'s closure inputs, the returned `WaveLength -> ComplexRefractionIndex` MUST agree with `OpticalProperties/Dispersive.fs` `Silicon().opticalProperties` at three test wavelengths within 1e-9.
- AC-D5: After building a uniaxial entry from (n_o, n_e), the constructed `Eps` MUST equal `Eps.fromComplexRefractionIndex (n_o, n_e, n_o)` (`MaterialProperties.fs:87`) element-by-element within 1e-12.
- AC-D6: After serialising and reloading an `OpticalConstructorProject` element carrying a `defaultUnit`, the canonical SI datum MUST be byte-identical and the `defaultUnit` label MUST be preserved, proving the label does not alter the stored value.
- AC-D7: After requesting a material preview with the spectral axis toggled to eV, the plot data passed to `plotN11` MUST be the same canonical-meter `Range<WaveLength>` as the nm toggle (only axis labels/scale differ), confirming no re-storage of non-SI units.
- AC-D8: After a `DispersionModel` carrying `Some thermoOptic` is evaluated at an operating temperature `T` differing from `referenceTemperature`, the returned `ComplexRefractionIndex` MUST equal the isothermal index plus `dndT ¬∑ (T ‚àí referenceTemperature)`; with `thermoOptic = None` the evaluated index MUST be byte-identical to the isothermal result, and only `dndT`/`referenceTemperature` (in SI 1/K and K) MUST round-trip through the JSON `materialEntry` `$def` while the operating temperature MUST NOT be persisted.

### Part E acceptance

- AC-E1: After the operator enters wavelength, incidence angle, polarization, and ellipticity in the Source editor and commits, `SourceSpec.toIncidentLight` MUST return an `IncidentLightInfo` (Fields.fs:338) whose `waveLength.value` equals the entered wavelength converted to meters and whose polarization/ellipticity/angle match the inputs, within one recompute cycle.
- AC-E2: After choosing a non-nm/¬µm display unit (√Ö, mm, eV, or cm‚Åª¬π) for wavelength, the produced `WaveLength` (Fields.fs:280) MUST carry the value converted via the ¬ßA.10 boundary conversions and the domain model MUST store no non-SI unit, verified on save of the project JSON.
- AC-E3: After toggling a wavelength or angle input to Ranged, the Source editor MUST produce a `RangedVariable` (Variables.fs:42) of the matching case (WaveLengthRange/IncidenceAngleRange) handed unchanged to the sweep layer, with no new range type introduced.
- AC-E4: After selecting the RCP, LCP, or unpolarized preset in the Poincar√©/ellipse picker, the source MUST set Ellipticity ¬±1.0 (clamped via Ellipticity.create, Fields.fs:306) for RCP/LCP or Coherence.Unpolarized for unpolarized, and the live Stokes readout MUST be computed via EmField.stokesVector (FieldFunctions.fs:44).
- AC-E5: After attaching a SpectralProfile (Blackbody/D65/A/LaserLine/Imported) and a wavelength range, `SpectralProfile.sample` MUST return a list of (WaveLength, weight) pairs in canonical meters, one `IncidentLightInfo` per sample, with imported spectra read from a sidecar via FSharp.Data and not from a project `.binz`.
- AC-E6: After setting a ConeAcceptance with N samples, `ConeAcceptance.sample` MUST fan the base incidence angle into N weighted sub-angles and the combined result MUST be averaged on Stokes/intensity outputs (FieldFunctions.fs:44,69), not on field amplitudes; a collimated source MUST be represented by `cone = None`.
- AC-E7: After setting coherence to Incoherent, the source MUST be solved through the existing substrate-driven Multiple/MultipleEmFieldSystem path (Solvers.fs:152, Fields.fs:571) with no separate incoherent solver added; Unpolarized MUST be evaluated as the incoherent average of Polarization.s and Polarization.p (Fields.fs:322,323).
- AC-E8: After defining multiple SourceSpec values in `project.sources`, the combined illumination MUST be a weighted incoherent StokesVector sum (Fields.fs:584,586) of every expanded `IncidentLightInfo`, with no field-level summation across sources and no cached expansion list.
- AC-E9: After enabling a GaussianBeamSpec, `GaussianBeamSpec.angularSpectrum` MUST decompose the beam into weighted plane-wave incidence angles using the existing createGaussian (FourierTransform.fs:74) and FourierTransform (FourierTransform.fs:137), introducing no new FFT or Gaussian generator.
- AC-E10: After opening the element palette, the operator MUST be able to add a `ConstructorElement.Source` and open its editor in one click with no confirmation gate, and the Source panel MUST be reachable from the palette navigation.

### Part F acceptance

- AC-F1: After a wavelength scan is run over a `WaveLengthRange`, the analysis layer MUST return R, T, the s/p split (Rp/Rs/Tp/Ts), and A = 1‚àíR‚àíT for every sweep point, with A computed by `absorptance` reusing `Solution.func` and never re-invoking the solver.
- AC-F2: After the user defines a thickness or material-parameter sweep, the analysis layer MUST drive it through an `ArbitraryVariableRange` `RangedVariable` and `Variables.calculate`, persisting the bulk `Solution` array ONLY as a `.binz` sidecar (Softellect `BinaryZippedFormat`), never in the canonical JSON.
- AC-F3: After a solution is computed, calling the completed `EmField.muellerMatrix` member MUST return the same matrix as `MuellerMatrix.fromEmFields`, and `stokesSystem`/`OpticalSystemSolver.muellerMatrixR()` MUST yield the incident/reflected/transmitted Stokes and reflected Mueller matrices without any re-derived 4√ó4 algebra.
- AC-F4: After a solution is computed, `degreeOfPolarization` MUST return sqrt(s1¬≤+s2¬≤+s3¬≤)/s0 from the existing reflected/transmitted `StokesVector`, and ellipticity/azimuth MUST be surfaced from the existing `EmFieldSystem` accessors with no new derivation.
- AC-F5: After a reflected solution is computed, `psiDelta` MUST return (Œ®, Œî) with tan Œ® = |r_pp/r_ss| and Œî = arg(r_pp/r_ss) from `amplitudeP`/`amplitudeS` of `solutionP()`/`solutionS()`, and `ncs` MUST return (cos 2Œ®, sin 2Œ® cos Œî, sin 2Œ® sin Œî).
- AC-F6: After a system is solved, `fieldDepthProfile` MUST return |E|¬≤ and Poynting samples versus depth (in meters) obtained by stepping the transmitted `EmField` through each `Layer` via `EmField.propagate`, without re-solving the 4√ó4 system per depth sample.
- AC-F7: After a system is solved, `layerAbsorptance` MUST return a per-`Layer` absorptance from the normal Poynting-flux drop across each layer, and `totalAbsorbedPower` MUST equal the system-level A from F.1 within solver tolerance.
- AC-F8: After a wavelength scan of an R or T channel, `spectrumToXyz`/`xyzToLab`/`xyzToSrgb` MUST return CIE XYZ, Lab, and an sRGB swatch computed from the embedded CIE 1931 colour-matching and illuminant tables, consuming the F.1 sweep output without re-running the solver.
- AC-F9: After the user changes the convergence control, the analysis layer MUST thread the new `SolverParameters.numberOfReflections` into `OpticalSystemSolver` for thick Plate/Wedge substrates, with no other numerical threshold altered and the default remaining 3.

### Part G acceptance

- AC-G1: After `optimize` is called with an `OptimizationRequest` whose `method` is `LevenbergMarquardt`, the ALGLIB adapter MUST return an `OptimizationResult` (or `Result.Error`) without any ALGLIB type or exception crossing the G.1 interface boundary, within the request's `maxIterations`.
- AC-G2: After a `DesignParameter list` and a `float[]` solution vector are folded over a base `OpticalSystem`, the produced system MUST reflect each parameter (e.g. layer `Thickness` in canonical meters) with no value stored in a non-SI unit.
- AC-G3: After a [Core] local-refinement run on a target/merit set with a lower-bounded thickness of 0, the returned refined `OpticalSystem` MUST contain no negative `Thickness` and MUST satisfy each `Inequality` target's hinge to zero within tolerance.
- AC-G4: After loading measured R/T or Œ®,Œî CSV data and running inverse fitting, the resulting `FitTarget` sample points MUST be stored in meters via `WaveLength.value`, and the fit MUST reduce œá¬≤ below its initial value.
- AC-G5: After a fit completes, the `FitReport` MUST expose œá¬≤/MSE, a parameter correlation matrix, confidence intervals, and per-sample residuals, and MUST be writable as a `.binz` sidecar (never inside the canonical JSON project).
- AC-G6: After needle optimization inserts a layer, the films list MUST grow by exactly one `Layer` and the post-insertion merit value MUST be no greater than the pre-insertion value.
- AC-G7: After clicking Cancel on a running optimizer, the G.5/G.9 loop MUST stop cooperatively and the page MUST be able to Revert to the pre-fit working `OpticalSystem`; Cancel MUST be a distinct control from Start.
- AC-G8: After a fit completes, the result charts MUST refresh through `plotComparison` showing fit-vs-measured overlay without a manual reload.
- AC-G9: After running `LocalRefinement` with `LevenbergMarquardt` on the Wolfram reference R/T and Œ®/Œî cases, the converged parameters and final œá¬≤ MUST match the recorded Wolfram values within the stated test tolerance.

### Part H acceptance

- AC-H1: After a user requests an R/T/Œ®/Œî-vs-Œª (or angle) plot, the embedded ScottPlot 1D view MUST display one zoom/pan-enabled trace per visible `OpticalFunction` with engine `fullName` legend labels, without opening any browser tab.
- AC-H2: After two or more systems are selected for overlay, the comparison view MUST draw the chosen function from every system on one plot, each trace named `fullName (index)`, reusing `plotComparison`'s data layout and never calling `Chart.show`.
- AC-H3: After a user requests a R-vs-Œª√óangle surface, the WebView2-hosted Plotly.NET surface MUST render with contours enabled and the engine's documented X/Y axis-swap applied, sourced from `calculate3D`/`mapFun`.
- AC-H4: After a user changes axis range, scale (linear/log10), title, color, line style, gridlines, or per-trace visibility, the only mutated state MUST be the `ChartSettings` record, and the change MUST appear on the chart via the H.1 projection functions within one MVU update cycle.
- AC-H5: After a user switches an axis unit (e.g. nm‚ÜíeV), displayed tick values MUST convert via the ¬ßA.10 boundary functions while the stored series and `ChartSettings` remain canonical SI.
- AC-H6: After a user hovers the 1D plot, the readout MUST report the nearest series point; after invoking peak/min/FWHM/two-cursor-delta, it MUST return the correct extremum, FWHM, or ŒîX/ŒîY computed purely from the `SeriesData` array without re-solving.
- AC-H7: After a solution is available, the polarization-ellipse plot MUST draw the parametric ellipse from the engine `Ellipticity`/azimuth members, and the Poincar√© sphere MUST plot the normalized Stokes point from `Solution.stokesR`/`stokesT`.
- AC-H8: After a field-depth plot is requested for a layer, the depth profile MUST be sourced from Part F ¬ßF.6 `fieldDepthProfile` (sampled via `EmField.propagate`), with depth shown in the layer's display unit.
- AC-H9: After the color calculation supplies an (x,y,rgb) chromaticity, the CIE view MUST draw the 1931 horseshoe and plot the point with its sRGB swatch, without Part H computing any color-matching integration.
- AC-H10: After a dispersive material and wavelength range are chosen, the n,k/œÅ/Œµ dispersion plot MUST render from the engine `plotDispersion`/`plotN11`‚Ä¶`plotRho33` series bodies adapted to renderer-neutral arrays, with no `Chart.show` call and no re-derivation of the dispersion formulas.

### Part I acceptance

- AC-I1: After `saveProject path project` returns `Ok` and `openProject path` is called, the returned project MUST equal the original `OpticalConstructorProject` value (round-trip identity over canonical SI fields) within a single call, with no unit conversion applied to `Thickness`/`WaveLength.value`.
- AC-I2: After `deserializeProject` is given JSON that violates `optical-constructor-project.schema.json`, it MUST return `SchemaValidationError` carrying the JsonSchema.Net messages and MUST NOT return a bound project.
- AC-I3: After `openProject` is called on a file whose `schemaVersion` differs from the single shipped version, it MUST return `SchemaValidationError` and MUST NOT execute any migration path.
- AC-I4: After `writeSidecar` persists a sweep table, the file on disk MUST have the `.binz` extension and MUST be readable back by `readSidecar` to the identical value; attempting `writeSidecar` of an `OpticalConstructorProject` MUST be absent from the codebase.
- AC-I5: After the project JSON references a sidecar by relative path and the `.binz` file is missing, `openProject` plus a sidecar read MUST surface `SidecarMissing`/`BinzError` rather than throwing.
- AC-I6: After `writeAutosave name project` returns `Ok`, the user's `<name>.ocproj` MUST be unchanged on disk and a distinct `<name>.ocproj.autosave` MUST exist.
- AC-I7: After a destructive model edit followed by `undo`, `EditHistory.present` MUST equal the pre-edit project; a subsequent `redo` MUST restore the edited project; `undo` on empty history MUST return the input unchanged.
- AC-I8: After `exportCsv path (headers, rows)` returns `Ok`, the file MUST contain one header line of column names followed by one comma-separated line per row, and MUST NOT have re-invoked the solver.
- AC-I9: After `exportChartImage path Png handle` returns `Ok` for a Plotly.NET chart, the saved file MUST be produced by the chart library's own writer (no custom rasterizer in `OpticalConstructor.Storage`).
- AC-I10: After `importMaterials` reads a refractiveindex.info-style CSV via FSharp.Data, it MUST return `MaterialEntry list`; after `exportMaterials` writes a library, the produced JSON MUST validate against the `materialEntry` `$def`.
- AC-I11: After `appendRevision` is called twice on the same project folder, two numbered JSON snapshots MUST exist under `history/`, and `diffRevisions` over them MUST return a `ProjectDiff` with no external-VCS invocation.

### Part J acceptance

- AC-J1: After a user opens an `OpticalSystem` with finite films, a wedge substrate, and a non-normal incidence angle, the schematic view MUST render each film band scaled by its `Thickness` `double<meter>`, draw the `Substrate.Wedge` band with a sloped lower edge, label each thickness in the layer's per-element default unit, and draw the incident ray at `IncidentLightInfo.incidenceAngle`, all within one MVU `view` re-evaluation.
- AC-J2: After the user defines a unit cell of N layers and a repeat count R >= 1, `RepeatBuilder.expand` MUST yield exactly N*R ordinary `Layer` records in cell order assignable to `OpticalSystem.films`, with no new period/super-layer type in the model.
- AC-J3: After the user selects any of the six templates (AR, bandpass, beam splitter, polarizer, waveplate, DBR), a valid `OpticalConstructorProject` MUST be produced and opened through the schema-validated project-open path, with the DBR template's periodic stack produced via `RepeatBuilder.expand`.
- AC-J4: After a material is dragged from the library panel and dropped on a layer row, that layer's `Layer.properties` MUST be replaced by the resolved `OpticalProperties` via a single immutable MVU update while `Layer.thickness` is unchanged.
- AC-J5: After two or more systems are marked visible in the workspace, their curves MUST be overlaid via the engine's `plotComparison` (`Charting.fs:38`) with no Part-J-local overlay implementation.
- AC-J6: After the app restarts, the favorites board, recent-files list, last working folder, panel layout, and preferences MUST be restored from the JSON `EnvironmentSettings` file (schema-validated, not `.binz`); on validation failure the app MUST fall back to built-in defaults without attempting migration.
- AC-J7: After a user edits a default-unit or wavelength-range preference, the change MUST affect only display/boundary formatting and MUST NOT alter any stored `double<meter>` domain value; solver defaults MUST be expressed as the engine's `SolverParameters`.
- AC-J8: After the user switches theme or rearranges dockable panels, the new theme and panel layout MUST round-trip through `EnvironmentSettings` JSON; and the FuncUI clone MUST NOT be linked/built until the ¬ßA.6/¬ßA.9 audit passes, with its linking mechanism left unresolved by Part J.
- AC-J9: After a user enters a non-positive finite thickness, a repeat count < 1, or an empty/invalid wavelength range, the corresponding `Validation` validator MUST return `Result.Error` and surface the message inline, blocking commit, without throwing or coercing.
- AC-J10: After a sweep or fit is started, `JobRunner` MUST report progress as completed-points/iterations on a background worker, expose a single Start‚ÜíCancel toggle, cancel cooperatively within one inter-point/inter-iteration check, refresh results via MVU on completion, and write any derived artefacts only to the project sidecar directory (never the repo root).
- AC-J11: After the user opens a gallery entry, a shipped sample `OpticalConstructorProject` corresponding to an existing `Analytics/Examples/*.fsx` case MUST open through the schema-validated path, and the units glossary MUST state the ¬ßA.10 eV/cm‚Åª¬π conversions without re-implementing them; no `.fsx` is executed at runtime.
- AC-J12: After the user opens a multi-element system, the `SystemView3D` OpenTK viewport MUST render the placed `ConstructorElement`s to scale along the beam path and draw the reflected/transmitted beam segments read from the already-solved `EmFieldSystem.reflected`/`.transmitted` (`Fields.fs:553-554`), without re-solving the system, without re-deriving beam routing, and without storing any non-SI viewport coordinate back into the model.

